</TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><TT>Source:Bureau of Labor</TT></TD><TD
COLSTART="2"><TT>Statistics.</TT></TD><TD COLSTART="3"></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P>The restrained employment growth since March 1991 has  differed by industry,
occupation, and state.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     After the severe recession of the early 1980s,
manufacturing  jobs increased 7.7 percent from November 1982 to March 1989. 
Since the 1990 tax increase, manufacturing jobs have declined by  6.0 percent.
Retail trade jobs increased 21.2 percent from  November 1982 to May 1987
compared with only 7.9 percent from  March 1991 to September 1995.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Sixty-two percent of the net new jobs created since March  1991 have
been in the higher paying executive, administration,  management, and
professional specialty occupations. From 1990 to  1994, however, there was no
employment growth in mechanic and  repair occupations or administrative and
clerical occupations.  Employment actually declined in construction trade
occupations and  machine operator and assembler occupations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Since the end of the last recession, not all states have seen  jobs
increase. While non-farm jobs in the U.S. increased by 7.9  percent, California,
Connecticut, Hawaii, and New York all lost around  1 percent of their jobs. The
Rocky Mountain states of Arizona,  Colo
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 -->  rado, Idaho, Montana, Nevada, New
Mexico, and Utah,  however, saw their non-farm jobs increase by more than 17.9
percent. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Rising Living Standards Despite Higher Taxes</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A decline in average real cash wages since 1973 falsely suggests  a decrease
in the American standard of living. Some politicians  are using this narrow
definition of economic well-being to promote  the failed redistribution and
regulatory policies of big  government. Most workers are better off today
because their real  compensation and real per capita income continue to
increase. Real  compensation is a more accurate measure of the &quot;pay&quot;
American  workers receive because it includes benefits, such as health care and 
pension payments, as well as cash. The reason for this is that  workers are
taking home more of their pay in the form of tax-free  benefits than ever
before. Employee benefits accounted for 41.3 percent  of payroll costs in 1993,
up from almost 18.7 percent in 1951  and 36.6 percent in 1979.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#16">16</A>  Stagnating cash wages are a
concern,  but government should be focusing on policies that increase 
productivity and economic growth to raise take-home pay instead of  imposing
mandates, taxes, and regulations that limit employment  opportunities and wages.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>How have wages and compensation changed in recent years?   Specifically:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     After growing from 1948 to 1973, the average real hourly 
wage (that is, adjusted for inflation) has declined 10.1  percent.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#17">17</A>  This decline, however, has not
occurred in all industries. Real  average hourly earnings in the service,
finance, insurance, and real  estate industries have increased 1.6 percent and
6.7 percent since 1973.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     From 1978 to 1994, average annual pay adjusted for inflation 
increased 1.0 percent.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#18">18</A>  This
long-run increase, however, hides  significant growth differences in the
intervening years and  between states. For example, average annual pay decreased
3.0  percent from 1978 to 1980, then increased 5.9 percent from 1980 to  1988,
and then declined 1.7 percent from 1988 to  1994.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#19">19</A>  Further, since 1988 average
annual pay has increased in 13 states and the  District of Columbia and declined
in 37 states.
</P>
<P>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>As noted, hourly wages do not account for the increasing  frequency with
which employees receive their &quot;pay&quot; in the form  of untaxed fringe
benefits. Further, hourly wage data are limited  in the types of employees they
cover (68 percent of all  payroll jobs).<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#20">20</A>
 Compensation  or wages plus benefits  is a more  complete measure of the pay
American workers receive. Real  compensation, by any measure, continues to
increase. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     From 1950 to 1973, real hourly compensation increased an 
average of 3.2 percent per year.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#21">21</A>
 Since 1973, real hourly  compensation has increased an average of 0.4 percent
per year. The  problem is not that the average wage has declined, but that total
&quot;pay&quot;  has grown more slowly since 1973. This can be attributed to the
 slowdown in the growth of productivity, resulting in part from  the growth of
government regulations, mandates, and higher taxes   all of which reduce the net
value of a worker's output, leading to  a slowdown of wages. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Comparing the Bush/Clinton economic expansion with the  Reagan
expansion reveals that most measures of workers' pay and  compensation were
affected negatively by the two largest tax  increases in history.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WAGE AND COMPENSATION GROWTH <br>
LOW-TAX VS. HIGH-TAX ECONOMIC EXPANSIONS</B>
</P>
<TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1"></TD><TD COLSTART="2"><B>Reagan Expansion</B></TD><TD
