<P><B>Note:</B> Hourly Earnings = cash pay per hour, including  overtime pay
before taxes;</P>
<P><B>Weekly Earnings =</B> avg. hourly earnings  times avg. hours worked per
week; </P>
<P><B>Avg. Annual Pay =</B> cash pay +  bonuses + tips + cash value of meals
and lodging + employer  contributions to 401(k) plans;</P>
<P><B>Hourly Compensation Index =</B> wages  and salaries of workers +
employers' contributions for social  insurance and private benefit plans + an
estimate of wages, salaries,  and supplemental payments for the self-employed
divided by the  hours of work of all persons, including proprietors and unpaid 
family workers;</P>
<P><B>Per Capita Income =</B> National Income and Product  Account estimate of
disposable personal income per person; 
</P>
<P><B>NIPA Compensation =</B> National Income and Product Account estimate  of
total compensation to employees, including cash pay +  employer contributions
for Social Security and private pension, health,  and welfare funds;</P>
<P><B>NIPA Wage &amp; Salary Income =</B> National  Income and Product Account
estimate of total wages and salaries paid  to workers. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Sources:</B> Bureau of Labor Statistics and Bureau of  Economic
Analysis.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>More Americans Moving Up the Economic Ladder</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The dynamic U.S. economy is characterized by an  extraordinary 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 -->  degree of income mobility that
has been all but ignored in the  recent minimum wage and declining wage
controversy. The  notion that low-income or high-income groups are composed
mostly  of the same people over time is an illusion. Data on income  mobility
reveal that most workers' incomes increase over time. The  comparison of average
incomes by group would be meaningful only  if America were a caste society in
which the people comprising  one group remained constant over time. This is one
reason why  Americans with modest incomes tend to resist &quot;soak the rich&quot;
class  warfare arguments  they hope to be rich one day.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     During the 1980s, there was considerable upward mobility 
for those in the lower-income and middle-income  groups.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#22">22</A>  For example, from 1979 to 1988,
the income of 85.8 percent of  workers in the lowest income group had increased
enough to move them  up into a higher income group.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#23">23</A> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-      A worker in the lowest income group in 1979 was more likely  to have
moved into the top income bracket by 1988 than to have  remained in the bottom
group.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Income mobility is important, but direction is more important.  The
upward movement of workers in the lowest, second-lowest,  and middle-income
groups is much larger than the downward  movement. From 1979 to 1988, the income
of 60.1 percent of  workers in the second-lowest income group had increased
enough to  move them up into a higher income group, and 47.3 percent of  workers
in the middle group had moved up.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#24">24</A>

</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     More than 60 percent of all workers can point to a minimum  wage job
as their first job experience.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#25">25</A> 
Some 40 percent of  workers 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->  starting a minimum wage job
receive their first raise within  4 months, and 63 percent of those workers earn
20 percent  more than the minimum wage within 12 months.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#26">26</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The U.S. economy, while not without problems, thus remains  dynamic, open,
and productive enough to enable most Americans  in the bottom income groups to
work their way up the economic  ladder. What is needed is not more centralized
control, but policies  to ensure that this flexibility and opportunity are
extended as  widely as possible.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Job Security</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Workers remain concerned about job security, layoffs, and  corporate
downsizing. In 1995, companies announced layoffs of  almost 440,000 workers.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#27">27</A>  Announced layoffs in 1995 were
down  28 percent from the peak of 615,000 in 1993, but were still 45  percent
higher than 1990. Each month it seems the media report  another large layoff and
more stories about employees who fear they  will be next. For example:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;AT&amp;T will be letting go 40,000 more employees, or 13%
of  its entire staff, about 70% of them before the end of the year....  [I]n
today's business climate, we are all  temps.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#28">28</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>&quot;But even though downsizing appears to be taking a new form  at
America's biggest companies, labor market experts say the  outlook isn't getting
any brighter for workers concerned about job  security. When people see these
high-visibility layoffs, they ask  themselves, `Is my company next, and will I
be  involved?'&quot;<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#29">29</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>&quot;When you see somebody you know affected by the  downsizing, and you
see it right across the street, you say, Oh my God, I  could be next.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#30">30</A>
</P>
<P>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Although recent studies show that job security has declined,  particularly
for some groups,<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#31">31</A> it is important
to put layoff reports  in their proper perspective.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Even with all of the layoff announcements, the U.S. economy 
has managed to create 8.3 million net new jobs since March  1991. Most (58
percent) were in the higher paying managerial and  professional specialty
occupations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In December 1995, 74.6 percent of consumers reported that  jobs are either
plentiful or not hard to get, up from 52.2 percent in  December 1991.32  Only
25.4 percent reported that jobs are hard  to get, down from 47.8 percent in
December 1991.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The median duration of unemployment in November 1995 was  7.7 weeks, down
from 8.8 weeks in 1992. From June 1992 to  November 1995, the number unemployed
for 27 weeks or more  declined by 42 percent to 1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>75 percent of all displaced workers that lost their jobs  between January
1991 and December 1992 found new  jobs.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#33">33</A>
 Only 11.5 percent remained unemployed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Most displaced workers (53 percent) who found new jobs  were earning the
same as or more than their old job paid. Over 27  percent were earning 20
percent more.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#34">34</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>This is not to say that there are not problems. But the percentage  of
America's population that is working is at an all-time high.  Further, no
government, company, or union can guarantee  employment for life, higher wages,
or upward mobility. Employment  security in the 1990s and beyond will depend
upon an  individual's ability to adapt to the changing demands of jobs and the
job  market. Workers who will fare the best are those with a good  basic
education, a strong work ethic and communication skills, and  a willingness to
relocate.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Folly of Increasing the Minimum Wage</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>President Bill Clinton urged Congress in 1995 to pass  legislation to raise
the hourly minimum wage from $4.25 to $5.15 over  two years. Although the
President and other proponents of an  increase argue that a higher minimum wage
is needed to achieve &quot;a  minimum decent living wage&quot; for working
Americans, a  minimum wage hike in fact will destroy entry-level job 
opportunities<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#35">35</A> for the very
unskilled Americans proponents claim to be helping.  Further, it will do nothing
to increase the income of nonworking  families, while raising prices for both
the poor and non-poor. Instead  of considering a minimum wage hike, Congress
should focus on  tax and regulatory reforms to increase take-home pay and reduce
 the cost of creating jobs. Doing that will promote economic  growth with low
inflation, and increase employment opportunities  and wages for all Americans.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#36">36</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     Raising the minimum wage generally does not help 
low-income households.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#37">37</A>  The
reason?  Over half (54 percent) of the  increased income for minimum wage jobs
would go to youth and  spouses living in families earning two or more times the
poverty  level, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->  rather than to poor minimum wage
workers.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#38">38</A> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Employers' response to an increase in the minimum wage  will harm
workers.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#39">39</A>  Forced to pay higher
wages when  productivity has not increased, employers tend to reduce the rate of
new  hiring and postpone the replacement of employees who quit. They  will tend
to reduce hours (particularly for unskilled workers) or  replace lower-skilled
workers with higher-skilled workers as  low-skilled workers quit. They also may
consider reducing or eliminating  pay raises and bonuses for their other
employees.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Increasing the minimum wage to $5.15 would result in a loss  of around
400,000 entry-level jobs.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#40">40</A> 
Depending on the  overall economy, total employment may increase, but there will
be  fewer unskilled job opportunities available for Americans than there 
otherwise would have been.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Dismal Results of Government Job Training</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Because statistics indicate that more education leads to  better-paying
jobs, Congress and others assume that government job  training programs work.
Unfortunately, they do not. For example:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     A nationwide controlled study of Job Training and
Partnership  Act programs reported no significant effect on either the earnings 
of young women or their employment. For young men it was  worse: zero impact on
employment and a 7.9 percent negative effect  on earnings. Although the program
increased the hourly wages  of adult women by a modest 3.4 percent, it had no
significant  effect on women who were on welfare or were high school dropouts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     After two years, graduates of the Summer Training and  Employ
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  ment Program had no higher
graduation rates or grades than a  control group and were no more likely to be
working.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     A study of the Jobstart program reported no significant increase  in
employment or earnings for the total four-year study period or  for any
individual year. The program did not reduce the number  of enrollees on welfare
and had no effect on the overall arrest rate.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>After 30 years and hundreds of billions of taxpayer dollars  spent, only a
few dozen job training programs have been subjected  to rigorous examination for
effectiveness. The few studies that  have been conducted generally show a record
of failure. The  programs do not achieve their primary goal because there is
little, if  anything, government can do to alter what happens when  individuals
neglect their first 12 years of  education.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#41">41</A>  The billions of tax dollars spent
on government job training and public assistance  programs are too much too
late. Rather than focus on  consolidating programs into state block grants,
Congress must ask itself a  fundamental question: Why should we continue to
spend  taxpayer money on programs that don't work?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Alternative. </B>The way to improve wages for  lower-income workers
is not through an artificial increase in pay (with its  damaging side effects)
but through a real increase in productivity.  The more revenue a worker
generates for an employer (i.e., the  more productive the worker is), the more
he or she will be paid.  The federal government can increase productivity by: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Balancing the budget.</B> This will increase total domestic
 saving, lower interest rates, and increase investment. The growth in  capital
per worker is closely associated over time with the growth in  labor 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 -->  productivity.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Cutting the capital gains tax.</B> This will raise the expected rate  of
return on investment in the U.S. and provide an incentive for  both American and
foreign firms to put their capital to work here  with American workers. A
capital gains tax cut also will make  more venture capital available for
emerging technologies and for  research and development. Past reductions in the
capital gains  tax rate (1978 and 1981) stimulated the start-up of new
businesses  and the expansion of job opportunities. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Increasing the skills of the future workforce.</B> What is needed  is
fundamental change aimed at improving basic education  through school choice,
strengthening core curricula, and enabling  local educators to improve
discipline and set high expectations. In  addition, parents need to make their
children stay in school, do  their homework, and stay out of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Increasing the skills of the current workforce.</B> This could  include
tax-deferred or tax-free education savings accounts similar to  individual
retirement accounts, or enabling states and individuals  to use lump sum
unemployment insurance benefits for education  and training.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>How to Improve Workplace Safety at Less Cost</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Although Congress intended that the Occupational Safety  and Health
Administration (OSHA) and Mine Safety and Health  Administration (MSHA) assure
all workers safe and healthy  working conditions, the effectiveness of these
agencies in carrying out  their missions is questionable. Between 1942 and 1970,
before the  cre
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 -->  ation of OSHA, the total number
of work-related injuries in  the U.S. declined by 3 percent despite a rapidly
growing  workforce. Taking workforce expansion into account, the injury rate 
declined by 45 percent.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#42">42</A>  This is
because businesses' financial  incentives to make the workplace safe  including
the costs of lost  productivity, workers' compensation, and liability claims 
are much  stronger than any OSHA penalties.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#43">43</A>  Despite assertions to the 
contrary, OSHA is responsible for only a small portion of the decline in  injury
and fatality rates.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#44">44 
</A></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     With and without OSHA's burdensome regulations, 
workplace fatality rates have declined significantly. For at least 23 years 
before OSHA was created, the fatality rate had been  declining steadily. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Since 1973, two years after OSHA was created, the incidence  rate of
injuries severe enough to cause a lost workday has  remained relatively stable.
The rate of injuries not severe enough to cause  a lost workday declined in the
1970s but has remained fairly  stable since 1980. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>From rulemaking to enforcement, the regulatory nightmare  that businesses
face has made OSHA inspectors as feared as IRS  auditors.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#45">45</A>  Most employers maintain safe and
healthy workplaces,  but the Department of Labor seems more concerned with 
prosecuting employers and collecting penalties than with providing  accurate,
reliable compliance information. This means many employers  are reluctant to
call OSHA for assistance in making their  workplaces safer for fear of
triggering punitive inspections. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Taxpayers can and should get more workplace safety for  their 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 -->  hard-earned dollars.
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     The Maine 200 program offered 200 employers in the state 
the option of working as partners with OSHA to prevent  workplace injuries or
being subject to the traditional regulatory  enforcement program. Over 90
percent of the employers chose to participate  in this Labor Department
experimental program begun in the  Bush Administration. In the first 18 months
of the program, self  inspections by 200 employers resulted in the discovery and
correction  of three times the number of workplace hazards that had been 
discovered in all OSHA inspections in Maine in the previous eight years.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Because OSHA's bureaucratic culture and lawyers have put  the search
for completely risk-free workplaces and ease of  prosecution above common sense,
it can take ten or more years to complete  a rule.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#46">46</A>  OSHA's regulatory process would
be more timely and  less burdensome if focused initially on hazards that pose
the  greatest risk to the most workers. For example, it took OSHA eight  years,
from 1986 to 1994, to revise its fall protection safety  standard. Had OSHA
focused on specific fall hazards, such as the  stability of scaffolding, and
published a rule in two years, many  workplace injuries and fatalities could
have been prevented. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Significant reform is required to redefine the federal  government's role in
workplace safety. &quot;There are only enough federal  inspectors to inspect
even the most hazardous workplaces every  several years.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#47">47</A>  Vice President Gore's National
Performance  Review correctly recognized that an army of OSHA inspectors is 
neither necessary nor likely, given the federal budget situation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><P>&quot;A new approach is needed  one that refocuses
the  responsibility for ensuring worksite safety and health on the  workplace.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#48">48</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 24 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Explicitly redefining OSHA's mission towards compliance  assistance will
leverage employers' desire for safety and  dramatically improve workplace safety
and health. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration declared that its labor policy was  to improve
job prospects and to &quot;reinvent&quot; the Department of  Labor. In practice,
these well-intentioned themes resulted in higher  government spending on
ineffective programs, more mandates on  employers, and reinvention rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Family Leave.</B> The Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA), 
enacted in 1993, requires businesses employing more than 50  people to provide
12 weeks of unpaid leave to care for sick family  members or a newborn child.
Although well intentioned, even  unpaid leave can hurt workers in ways that are
not so apparent, since  there is a real cost to employers that is passed on to
workers.  Federally mandated benefits result in lost job opportunities and a 
reduction in real wages or other benefits  the opposite of what mandates  are
intended to accomplish.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#49">49</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>School-to-Work.</B> The School-to-Work Act, enacted in 1994,  provided
$250 million to the Departments of Education and Labor  for state grants and
national programs. States use the money to  devise state and local strategies
that link schools and the private sector  to help young people make the
transition from school to careers  or further their education, as well as to
develop new assessment  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->  accountability procedures. In
practice, however, the  School-to-Work Act increases federal control and
involvement in  public schools and will encourage student counselors to funnel 
children into government-knows-best career paths, limiting individual  and
parental choice.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Striker Replacement.</B> Under the striker replacement executive  order
(E.O. 12954), issued in March 1995, any federal  contractor who hires permanent
striker replacement workers is subject to  termination of the contract or
debarment from bidding on future  contracts. The $100,000 annual threshold<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#50">50</A> effectively extends  coverage to
contractors receiving 90 percent of federal contracts  and will raise the cost
of federal contracts as these employers  are forced to take into account the
potential cost of settling labor  disputes. The Employment Policy Foundation
estimates the  annual economic cost of implementing the order at between $520 
million and $2 billion.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#51">51</A> 
Further, the order increases the likelihood  of strike activity at federal
contractors, hurting both union  workers and employers through lost wages and
output, and may  discourage unionized employers from even bidding on federal
contracts.  By increasing the incentive for businesses to set up nonunion 
subsidiaries and encouraging the use of nonunion subcontractors, it  ultimately
hurts union workers' income and job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>On February 2, 1996, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District  of Columbia
unanimously set aside President Clinton's striker  replacement executive order.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#52">52</A>  The court ruled that E.O. 12954 
is regulatory in nature and is pre-empted by federal labor law  that guarantees
the right to hire permanent replacement workers.  The President has instructed
the Justice Department to take all  appropriate steps to have the decision
overturned.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reinventing Government.</B> Both the National Performance  Review (NPR),
released in September 1993, and DoL's own  reinventing efforts are supposed to &quot;make
government work better and  cost less.&quot;  The NPR estimated that DoL could
save American  taxpayers $252 million out of $68 billion in discretionary
spending  over six years by implementing 21 reinvention  recommendations.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#53">53</A>  Further, in response to
congressional initiatives to reform the  Occupational Safety and Health
Administration, President  Clinton announced additional OSHA reinvention
activities in May  1995. According to the White House, OSHA will &quot;fundamentally
 change its operation from one of command-and-control to one that  builds
partnerships among regulators and business. Secondly, OSHA  will eliminate or
fix out-of-date and confusing standards and  instead identify clear and sensible
priorities. Finally, OSHA will target  the most serious hazards and dangerous
workplaces.... &quot; 
<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#54">54</A> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfortunately, DoL's reinvention actions have not matched  its rhetoric.
Although DoL has made some improvements, most  have been relatively minor
changes.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#55">55</A>  The problem is that &quot;the
 federal government is not simply broke; it is  broken.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#56">56</A>  Tinkering with the process of
government rather than addressing the substance  of what government does is not
real reform.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#57">57</A>  Further, OSHA's 
lack of commitment to and accountability for real reform is  underscored by its
recent efforts to discourage Congress from  codifying its own reinvention ideas
into law.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#58">58</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE 104TH CONGRESS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unlike the White House, Congress has been addressing labor  law reform
vigorously. The 104th Congress has dealt with a variety  of 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 -->  bills to reform and update
America's labor laws, addressing  issues that have been neglected for years. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Job Training.</B> Both the Senate and the House passed
legislation  to consolidate over 70 of the 163 federal job training programs 
into state block grants and reduce overall spending by almost 20  percent. The
legislation gave states the flexibility to design  unified employment,
education, and economic development programs  that meet the needs of their
workers. It also significantly improved  federal and state performance
accountability. The Senate and  House versions of the legislation are
significantly different, and  those differences are being reconciled in a
conference committee. A  final version of the job training legislation is
expected to go to  the President for his signature this year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Pay and Hours.</B> Both the House and Senate have introduced bills  to
reform the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA). This is the  statute that sets the
minimum wage, overtime pay, and child labor  standards affecting more than 113
million workers. The bills  would allow workers and employers to reach voluntary
agreements  concerning flexible work schedules and pay. For example, a  mother
would be able to work 45 hours one week in exchange for  working 35 hours the
next week so that she could have time to take  her child to the doctor.
Currently, the FLSA bars employers from  providing this flexibility, even to
salaried workers, by requiring  the payment of overtime and prohibiting the
shifting of hours  from one week to the next.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#59">59</A>  Both houses are planning
additional  hearings in 1996.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Workplace Health and Safety.</B> A number of bills were  introduced in
the House and Senate to reform workplace safety and  health programs. The
leading House bill is H.R. 1834, introduced  by Representative Cass Ballenger
(R-NC). In the Senate, the  leading bill is S. 526, introduced by Senator Judd
Gregg (R-NH). Of  these two bills, H.R. 1834 represents the more comprehensive 
OSHA reform. It would focus more of OSHA's resources on  compliance assistance
instead of enforcement, give employers a  reasonable time to fix hazards before
a penalty is issued, and restore  common sense and sound science to the way OSHA
writes its standards.  It also is the only bill that consolidates administrative
overhead  and ends duplicative costs by merging OSHA and MSHA. S. 526 
essentially proposes to codify many of OSHA's reinvention  initiatives.
Although, the Senate Labor Committee has reported out  S. 526, the House has not
yet marked up H.R. 1834. In  February, Vice President Al Gore promised the
AFL-CIO that  President Clinton would veto either bill this year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Davis-Bacon.</B> Both the Senate and the House have introduced  bills to
repeal the Davis Bacon Act. Davis-Bacon was enacted  during the Depression
explicitly to prevent low-skilled nonunion  workers  chiefly blacks and
Hispanics  from competing for  federally funded construction jobs. Unfortunately
for these workers, it  has succeeded. This Depression-era law promotes racial 
discrimination in the construction industry, needlessly costs taxpayers billions
 of dollars each year, stifles productivity, and subsidizes special  interests.
Moreover, states are beginning to investigate reports  of fraudulently submitted
data that inflate U.S. DoL prevailing  wage determinations.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#60">60</A>  The Senate Labor Committee
reported out  its Davis-Bacon repeal bill last year, but the House has not yet 
acted on its version. Additional House hearings on Davis-Bacon  are scheduled
for 1996.  
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Collective Bargaining.</B> Both the Senate and the House also  have
introduced bills to reform the National Labor Relations Act.  The House-passed
Teamwork for Employees and  Management (TEAM) Act would enable businesses to
establish  employer-employee involvement committees as a way to give workers a 
voice in business operations to help improve productivity, safety,  and customer
service. Currently, the only discussions of  workplace issues between employers
and workers that are clearly legal  are those that occur during traditional
collective bargaining;  businesses that establish employee-employer committees
risk  litigation and significant legal costs. The Senate is expected to vote on 
its version of the TEAM Act in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The National Right-to-Work Act (S. 581 and H.R. 1279) seeks  to preserve and
protect the free choice of individual employees  to form, join, or assist labor
organizations, or to refrain from  such activities. Congressional hearings on
this bill are planned for  1996, and the bill faces strong opposition from
organized labor.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>ERISA.</B> The Employee Retirement and Income Security  Act (ERISA) was
enacted in 1974 to protect the assets in  employee pension and welfare plans<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#61">61</A> that provide workers with 
retirement benefits promised by their employers. Reform legislation in  the
104th Congress has focused on the regulation of health  insurance benefits. In
the House, Representative Harris Fawell (R-IL)  introduced a bill (H.R. 995)
which would provide for health  insurance portability between jobs, increased
participation, and other  consumer protections for workers. In the Senate, Nancy
 Kassebaum (R-KS) has introduced S. 1028, which incorporates sections  of H.R.
995 dealing with increasing access to health care  benefits, providing for
greater portability of health insurance between  jobs, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 30 -->  increasing the security of health
care benefits for workers,  and increasing the purchasing power of individuals
and small  employers. S. 1028 was approved by the Senate Labor Committee in 
October 1995. It is highly likely that health insurance reform will  be enacted
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A few bills reforming ERISA's pension provisions also were  introduced in
Congress. The most comprehensive (H.R. 2037 and  S. 1006), introduced by
Representative Rob Portman (R-OH)  and Senator David Pryor (D-AR), would
simplify pension  provision and distribution rules and improve access to pension
plans  for small employers. It is highly likely this pension law reform will  be
enacted by the 104th Congress in 1996.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Labor Department Reforms.</B> Congress also used the budget  process
last year as a vehicle for reform. The House voted to reduce  FY 1996 DoL
discretionary spending by 13.8 percent and  instituted several important
reforms. Among these, the House budget  prohibits the issuance of two
unnecessarily burdensome OSHA  regulations on ergonomics and fall protection,
and bars DoL from  promoting &quot;economically targeted investments&quot; by
private  pension plans.  Both the Senate and House most likely will pass a 
continuing resolution that will fund DoL for the remainder of FY  1996 with a 15
percent spending cut from FY 1995.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Congress should undertake a fundamental reform of  America's labor laws.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#62">62</A>  The primary objectives of this
effort should be to: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Reduce </B>excessive burdens on businesses, job
opportunities,  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 31 -->  real wage growth while
maintaining workplace health and safety;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Improve</B> labor market flexibility while maintaining basic  employment
protections; and 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Strengthen</B> and expand workers' rights to work at home, to join  or
not join unions, and to form employee-employer committees  to improve
productivity, quality, and customer service.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Specifically, Congress should:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Close down the Department of Labor.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The best way to achieve reform is to close down the  Cabinet-level
department and move its legitimate national functions into  sub-Cabinet agencies
or other departments. Other functions that are  not national in scope should be
devolved to the states, or in some  cases to the private sector. Obsolete,
ineffective, and wasteful rules  and programs should be repealed or closed down.
The Department  of Labor has gone far beyond its original  mandate<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#63">63</A> and has become a burdensome and
feared regulatory agency that presents  significant barriers to creating jobs
and increasing real wages. The  proliferation of mandated benefits and workplace
requirements  makes most small businesses think very carefully before hiring 
additional workers. Overzealous enforcement has made DoL the enemy  of American
business and the American worker. Congress should  do what the Clinton
Administration promised but failed to do   reform this overgrown and intrusive
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Devolve the unemployment insurance system to the states. 
</B><!-- Generation of PM publication page 32 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Moving the unemployment insurance system to the states  should be part of
the closure strategy. This would enable states to  take action to decrease the
duration of unemployment, reduce  payroll taxes, and increase jobs. Devolution
should include the  Veterans Employment Service, labor market information
projects, the  one-stop career center concept, and the administration of 
unemployment insurance. Congress also should devolve the Federal  Extended
Benefit program, repeal Trade Adjustment Assistance,  and provide incentives for
states to overhaul and integrate  employment services and to reduce the duration
of unemployment payments  by moving the unemployed into new jobs more quickly. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Consolidate more job training programs into state block grants  and
focus funding on job placement assistance. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Congress recently consolidated over 70 of 163 job training  programs into
state block grants.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#64">64</A>  Although
this was a good  first step, more programs should be consolidated and the
funding  focused on job placement assistance. Conventional wisdom says  that
most job training programs work. Unfortunately, they do  not.65  Rather than
consolidate ineffective programs, Congress  should recognize that federal job
training programs simply do not  work and end them.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#66">66</A>  One thing is clear from the few
rigorous  studies that have been done: Government can do little, if anything, to
 alter the effect of its citizens' neglecting their first 12 years of 
education. The billions of dollars spent on government job training  and public
assistance programs are too much too late. What is  needed is fundamental reform
of the school system so that young  Americans enter the workforce with the basic
skills and attitudes  they need to succeed.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 33 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reform the Occupational Safety and Health  Administration (OSHA) and
transfer the Mine Safety and Health  Administration (MSHA) to OSHA. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This reform is needed to redefine the federal government's role  in
workplace safety and health and &quot;refocus the responsibility  for ensuring
worksite safety and health on the  workplace.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#67">67</A>  Merging MSHA with a reformed OSHA
is a sensible first step toward  improving workplace health and safety, limiting
unnecessary  government intervention, and reducing inefficient, wasteful 
government spending. Businesses already have much stronger financial  incentives
than OSHA penalties, such as the costs of lost  productivity, workers'
compensation, and liability claims, to maintain and  continually improve the
safety of their workplaces. Thus, the role  of the federal government should be
redefined from that of  heavy-handed regulator to one of cooperative partner.
Congress  also should spin off the &quot;new&quot; OSHA as a separate 
sub-Cabinet agency.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Repeal Davis-Bacon and the Service Contract Act. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Davis-Bacon Act was enacted during the Depression  explicitly to prevent
low-skilled nonunion workers  chiefly blacks  and Hispanics  from competing for
federally funded  construction jobs.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#68">68</A>
 This Depression-era law contributes to racial  discrimination in the
construction industry, needlessly costs taxpayers  billions of dollars a year,
stifles productivity, and subsidizes  special interests. Moreover, states are
beginning to investigate reports  of fraudulently submitted data that inflate
U.S. DoL prevailing  wage determinations and drive up the cost of federally
funded  construction projects.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#69">69</A> 
If Davis-Bacon were not already law, it  would 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 34 -->  never be passed today. Proponents
would be denounced as  supporting discrimination; it would be pointed out that
the  bill's worker protection provisions are unnecessary because they exist  in
other statutes; and lawmakers would object to the heavy,  unnecessary budget
costs imposed by the legislation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Service Contract Act (SCA) artificially inflates the cost  of federal
service contracts by as much as $500 million per year  and, like Davis-Bacon,
creates an unfair barrier for many unskilled  entry-level workers, who tend to
be poor and minorities. DoL  has long been criticized for the way it operates
under this law.  Despite two amendments,<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#70">70</A>
the SCA continues to suffer from  statutory ambiguity, administrative problems,
arbitrary requirements,  and capricious enforcement.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#71">71</A>  The General Accounting Office 
has recommended repealing the SCA because of DoL's &quot;inability  to
administer the act efficiently and effectively&quot; and because &quot;it  is
impractical, in our opinion, to make `prevailing wage'  determinations under the
act in a consistently equitable  manner.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#72">72</A>  Outdated by extension of the Fair
Labor Standards Act to service  workers, the SCA has become an unnecessary and
costly bureaucratic  burden that should be repealed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reform the Fair Labor Standards Act to allow employers to  offer
flexible schedule and compensation options.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) was enacted to protect  unskilled,
low-pay workers. But in today's economy, where  both parents are likely to be
working, its rigid and inflexible  provisions hurt more than they help. The FLSA
deprives workers of the  right to order their daily lives, both on and off the
job, to meet the  responsibilities of work and home. For example, a worker  who

<!-- Generation of PM publication page 35 -->  wants to work 35 hours one week
in exchange for working  45 hours the following week to attend a child's
parent-teacher  conference must forgo five hours of pay or else have an employer
 willing to pay overtime for working more than 40 hours the second  week.
Congress should extend the same freedom to private workers  that federal
employees have  flextime  and allow employers to  offer flexible schedule and
compensation options to their  workers.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#73">73
</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Repeal the Norris-LaGuardia Act to remove union special  privileges.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Norris-LaGuardia Act (NLA), passed in 1932, exempts  unions from the
Sherman Antitrust Act, makes union-free  employment contracts unenforceable in
federal courts, and prohibits  federal judges from issuing injunctions to
interrupt violent strikes.  The NLA is special privilege legislation for
organized labor and  should be repealed.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#74">74</A>
 If there are to be antitrust laws, they ought to  apply equally to all
combinations in restraint of trade, whether by  employers or by workers. The
right of workers and employers to  enter voluntarily into union-free contracts
should not be abridged,  and workers and employers should be able to petition
the courts to  stop union-related violence. While there is room in a free
society  for voluntary unionism, there is no room for the special  privileges
granted unions under the NLA.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reform the National Labor Relations Act to remove restrictions  on the
ability of employers to create employee involvement  structures and to protect
the free choice of individual workers to form  and join unions, or to refrain
from such activities.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Employer-employee involvement (EI) committees are a way  to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 36 -->  give workers a voice in business
operations to help improve  productivity, safety, and customer service. Under
current law,  however, the only discussions of workplace issues that are clearly
 legal between employers and employees are those that occur in  traditional
collective bargaining arrangements. In practice,  employers can listen to their
nonunion employees but cannot respond to  their views without risking litigation
and significant legal costs.  The Commission on the Future of Worker-Management 
Relations<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#75">75</A> has recommended &quot;removing
the legal  uncertainties&quot;<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#76">76</A>
on the EI committees that take a broader, more systemic approach to 
participation that the evidence suggests has the greatest long-term  positive
effects on economic performance. Congress should reform  the National Labor
Relations Act (NLRA) to exempt EI  committees formed to address issues of
quality, productivity, safety, and  customer service.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Section 7 of the NLRA limits the right of workers to refrain  from union
activities if there is a collective bargaining agreement  that requires union
membership as a condition of employment.  Forcing a worker to join or pay dues
to an unwanted union amounts to  deprivation of the First Amendment guarantee of
freedom of  association. According to the NLRA, a worker has full freedom of 
rights except when compulsory unionism enters the picture. The  exception clause
in Section 7 should be repealed.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Ban the diversion of union dues for political or ideological  purposes
to which employees object.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The U.S. Supreme Court ruled in 1988 that unions, as  exclusive bargaining
agents, may not use proceeds from dues to pursue  political or ideological goals
over the objections of affected  employ
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 37 -->  ees. The proceeds from those
employees, said the Court, are to  be used strictly for collective bargaining
and contract  administration, including grievance adjustment.<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#77">77
</A></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Dues are mandatory even for employees who are not members  of the union but
who may be required, under the NLRA principle  of exclusive representation, to
support it. Federal legislation  is needed to require the written authorization
of workers for  unions to use dues or dues equivalents for political purposes.
Such  legislation should place the burden on unions to prove that no funds  are
being diverted without written consent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Take action to boost productivity, thereby increasing  compensation.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Contrary to the practitioners of class warfare, employers do not   indeed,
cannot  unfairly keep down the wages of their  lower-skilled and entry-level
employees. Employers, as well as  employees, operate within a competitive labor
market in which wage  rates broadly reflect the productivity of workers  
<I>less </I>the costs of government-imposed mandates and taxes associated with
employing  a worker. The more productive a worker is, the more that  worker will
be paid. Congress should focus on policies that will  increase wages and job
opportunities for Americans by improving  labor productivity and reducing the
cost of employing workers.  Specifically, Congress should:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Balance the budget.</B> This will increase total domestic
saving,  lower interest rates, and increase investment. The growth in capital 
per worker is closely associated over time with the growth in  labor
productivity.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 38 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Cut the capital gains tax.</B> This will increase investment in the 
U.S. and provide an incentive for both American and foreign firms  to put their
capital to work here with American workers. A  capital gains tax cut also will
make more venture capital available  for emerging technologies and for research
and development that  will improve future productivity.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Increase the skills of the workforce.</B> What is needed is  fundamental
change aimed at improving basic education through  school choice, strengthening
core curricula, and enabling local  educators to improve discipline and set high
expectations. Congress  also should consider tax-deferred or tax-free education
savings  accounts similar to individual retirement accounts, or enabling  states
and individuals to use lump sum unemployment insurance  benefits for education
and training.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Enact significant regulatory reform.</B> The explosion of new 
regulations since 1988 has raised the cost of labor and capital,  created
barriers to the formation of new companies and jobs, and  raised the cost of
employing Americans. This higher cost of  employment in turn means that in a
competitive economy, the return to labor  in the form of wages is reduced. The
regulatory burden needs to  be rolled back, not only to allow wages to rise, but
also to  decrease the cost of hiring workers.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>The White House also should take action. Specifically, the  President
should:
</P>
<P><B>Rescind the striker replacement executive order. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Executive Order 12954, signed by President Clinton in  March 1995, was an
attempt to bypass Congress and establish new  labor 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 39 -->  policy by executive fiat: a gift
to a constituency that could not  get its way through the legislative process.
The order will drive up  the cost of federal contracts and hurt workers. The
$100,000  annual threshold effectively extends coverage to contractors receiving
 90 percent of federal contracts and will raise the cost of federal  contracts
as employers take into account the potential cost of  settling labor disputes.
The economic cost of implementing the order  will be between $520 million and $2
billion.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#78">78</A>  Further, the order 
will increase the likelihood of strike activity that hurts both  union workers
and employers through lost wages and output, and  may even discourage unionized
employers from bidding on federal  contracts in the future. It also will
increase the incentive for  businesses to set up nonunion subsidiaries and
encourage the use of  nonunion subcontractors  both of which ultimately hurt
union workers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Although the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of  Columbia unanimously
set aside President Clinton's striker replacement  executive order,<A
HREF="ftnt5.htm#79">79</A> the President has instructed the
Justice  Department to take all appropriate steps to have the decision
overturned.  The President should not waste Justice Department resources on 
this appeal and should rescind E.O. 12954.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q &amp; A</A></B></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What should the government do to create and keep jobs in  this
country?  What do you say to the millions of Americans  looking for work?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B>  Outdated labor laws, mandates, and heavy taxes lock  workers out
of jobs the private sector otherwise would create.  Congress needs to balance
the budget, cut taxes, and eliminate  unnecessarily 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 40 -->  burdensome regulations. This will
improve economic growth,  create more job opportunities, and increase the
take-home pay  of American workers. Government mandates and wasteful rules  are
strangling job creation, making employers think twice before  hiring additional
workers. Americans want jobs, and employers  want to hire them. Red tape and
taxes get in the way.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Compared with the 1980s, the burden of higher taxes and  more regulations
has limited job growth significantly. Since the  1990 and 1993 tax increases,
manufacturing jobs have declined by  6.0 percent. We need to reduce government
spending, cut taxes  for American families, and reduce the capital gains tax to 
increase investment, productivity, wages, and jobs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. How can you support cutting taxes and regulations on big  business
when wages are falling, corporate profits are up, and  executive pay is
excessive?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A. </B>The problem is not that profits are too high; profits are  needed
to invest in new ventures which create jobs and raise  productivity  and wages.
The problem is that taxes, mandates, and  regulations are keeping workers' pay
too low. Cutting individual taxes  will increase the take-home pay of working
Americans. If you look  at your paycheck, you'll see that the real culprit is
the  government, not your employer. Cutting taxes boosts take-home pay  without
cutting job opportunities. For instance, Congress's  $500-per-child tax credit
would put $22 billion per year back into family  budgets so that working parents
can provide for their children in a way  no government program can. The other
key to higher wages is  productivity. Lowering the capital gains tax will
increase  investment, improve productivity, and increase wages. Balancing the 
budget 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 41 -->  and cutting taxes will help poor
and middle-class Americans  more than any other factor.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. The minimum wage is too low. You can't make ends meet  unless you
work two jobs; what's the harm in raising the  minimum wage?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B>  It's a job killer and will hurt the very people it is suppose 
to help. The reason: Telling an employer that he or she must  pay higher wages
to low-skilled, entry-level workers simply means  the employer will hire fewer
such workers. Minimum wage laws  presume that politicians are morally justified
in destroying  some people's jobs and their opportunity to begin living the 
American dream in order to inflate other people's wages. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Isn't allowing companies to use replacement workers  during strikes
just a ploy to break unions?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> It is striker replacement law that ultimately hurts union 
workers and drives up the cost of federal contracts. Outlawing  replacement
workers will simply increase the incentive for businesses to set  up nonunion
companies and encourage the use of nonunion  subcontractors.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Most conservatives said that NAFTA would be a good thing  for U.S.
workers. What do you say now to those Americans who  have lost their jobs to
cheap Mexican labor?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Policies that cause the economy to change and grow  always mean
some jobs are lost while many new ones are created.  Some jobs indeed have been
lost because of NAFTA, but many  more 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 42 -->  have been created. NAFTA is good
for American workers  because free trade creates jobs, increases wealth, and
offers  consumers more and better goods at lower prices. It is protectionism
that  ultimately destroys jobs, reduces wealth, and limits consumer  choice.
Free trade may lead to the demise of some businesses and jobs,  but so does
local competition. What is most important is that free  trade fosters higher
productivity, and higher productivity  generates higher wages, more wealth, and
more jobs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Doesn't curbing OSHA mean more worker injuries and deaths?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Everyone wants better workplace safety and health. The issue  is
how you get there. A new approach is required to improve the  incentives for
workplace health and safety. The role of the  federal government needs to be
changed from that of heavy-handed  regulator to that of cooperative partner.
Today's army of OSHA  inspectors focuses on fines and penalties. That does not
mean  work. Instead, the government should work cooperatively with  businesses
and employees to improve workplace safety. OSHA's  own Maine 200 program has
proven that emphasizing compliance  assistance over enforcement can improve
workplace safety  and health dramatically. If we take this course, Americans
will  get more workplace health and safety for their tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Doesn't somebody who has worked all his life and is  suddenly laid
off deserve help with some job training?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Yes. The problem is that today's federal job training  programs
are ineffective. The 104th Congress is working on legislation  that consolidates
over 70 of the 163 federal job training programs  scattered across 15 agencies
into state block  grants.<A HREF="ftnt5.htm#80">80</A>  This
will help, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 43 -->  because states will have the
flexibility to design unified  employment, education, and economic development
programs that  meet the job training needs of their workers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Why do conservatives want to close down the Department  of Labor? 
Who will protect workers' interests in Washington?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> American labor law is largely a product of the conditions  and
perspectives of the 1930s and needs to be reformed.  Today's economy, labor
market conditions, and labor-management  relations differ significantly from
those that existed when most  of America's major labor laws were passed. Workers
are  demanding more flexible hours, pay, and working conditions than current 
laws and regulations allow. Employers are straining under  unnecessarily
burdensome regulations, mandates, lawsuits, and taxes.  American labor laws
should be reformed to empower workers to  protect themselves. The problem is
that the whole philosophy and  organization of the Department of Labor is
steeped in the 1930s and  resists modernization.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Conservatives are not calling for the elimination of  everything DoL does.
Instead, they are calling for functions to be carried  out elsewhere. Some of
DoL's key national functions, like  workplace health and safety, would remain at
the federal level. Other  functions that are not national in scope should be
turned over to  the states, or in some cases to the private sector where they
can be  run more effectively. Obsolete, ineffective, and wasteful 
bureaucracies, however, should be closed. 
</P>

<a name="EXP"><b>EXPERTS</b></a><p>

