<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 9</h3>
<center>
<h2>
EDUCATION
</H2>
<P>
<CITE><B>By <a href="/heritage/staff/doyle.html">Denis P. Doyle</a> </B></CITE>
<P>
<A HREF="chpt9.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt9.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt9.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt9.html#Q&A
">Q&amp;A</A> | <a href="chpt9.html#SELECTED">Selected Heritage Foundation Studies</a>  | <a href="chpt9.html#EXP">Experts</a> 
</center><p>
<a href="educ_1.gif">Chart 1</a>: SAT Scores Dropped 60 Points in Past 3 Decades<br>
<a href="educ_2.gif">Chart 2</a>: In Math, Science Tests, American 13-Year-Olds Lag Behind Other Industrial Countries<br>
<a href="educ_3.gif">Chart 3</a>: Where the Money to Pay Americorps "Volunteers" Comes From<br>
<a href="educ_t1.gif">Table 1</a>: Total Education Expenditures in U.S.<br>
<a href="educ_t2.gif">Table 2</a>: Total Public Expenditures, Elementary and Secondary Institutions<br>
<a href="educ_t3.gif">Table 3</a>: Federal Spending on Elementary, Secondary Education<br>
<a href="educ_t4.gif">Table 4</a>: Annual Expenditures Per Pupil, Public Elementary, Secondary Schools<br>
<a href="educ_t5.gif">Table 5</a>: Spending Per Pupil and National Test Results -- More Money Doesn't Mean Better Results<br>
<a href="educ_t6.gif">Table 6</a>: Current Public Expenditures for Primary Education by School Level and Country<br>
<a href="educ_t7.gif">Table 7</a>: Percent of Families Who Enroll Children in Private School, by Race, Ethnicity<br>
<a href="educ_t8.gif">Table 8</a>: Americorps "Volunteers" in Federal Bureaucracies<br>
<p><a href="chpt9text.html">Additional Text</a><p>

<P><B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES
</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>American education continues to be in crisis. Government  spending on
education has skyrocketed even as school performance  and student achievement
have remained static, leaving young  Americans ill-equipped to function in
today's increasingly  competitive world.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The liberal solution, as always, is more money, more  bureaucracy, more
regulation, more federal intrusion. Candidates need to  emphasize that America's
education crisis cannot be solved by  central government decree. Schools will
not be improved by letting  Washington run them. The crisis can be solved only
by taking  power away from centralized bureaucracies and empowering  parents,
teachers, principals, and local school boards to take charge  and make things
better for their own communities. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The most important education goal of the 1990s is to put  parents and
teachers in charge of education  at the local level. In  the nation's large
cities in particular, public schools have  become faceless monopolies,
insensitive or indifferent to parental  and teacher concerns about quality,
standards, and discipline.  Public schools must be made fully accountable to the
parents and  children they are meant to serve. That means parents  especially 
low-in
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->  come parents  must be given the
power to transfer their  children to, and the public funds to educate their
children, in other public  or private schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>High academic standards lie at the heart of effective  education. But
standards must reflect America's tradition of local  control: They should be
locally adopted and adapted to local needs  and capacities. While education is a
national issue, it is a local  responsibility. Federal &quot;remedies&quot; are
barriers to needed innovation  and reform, not the solution. Indeed, the
original genius of the  federal system was that the states were &quot;laboratories
of democracy.&quot;   Each state, and each local school district, can learn from
the others.  The federal push to establish fashionable outcomes-based 
education, and the reaction it has precipitated, should remind us that the 
federal role should be minimal and non-interventionist.  Decisions need to be
made in local schools and the communities they serve.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Moreover, since the time of the ancient Greeks, schools have had  a central
mission which embodies but goes beyond academics:  character formation. Students
should become better people by virtue  of attending school; habits of hard work,
honesty, self-respect,  and respect for others are essential to democratic
capitalism,  and schools should support their development as ardently as they 
support mastery of mathematics and English. The public school  in America once
proudly carried out that function  now  many schools undermine it. There is, as
well, a pressing practical  issue: Schools must be safe and secure learning
environments for  students, teachers, and other members of the education 
community. The lesson should be clear: Learning is important, self-discipline 
is important, and standards of behavior will be enforced, just as  academic
standards will.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Adopting institutional reforms centered around school choice  for parents,
autonomy for teachers and principals, and genuine  teacher professionalism can
change the system's fundamental  incentives. Today's government- and
union-controlled monopoly can be  replaced with a diverse and flexible system
controlled by  parents. The result will be freedom of choice for parents,
teachers, and  students, greatly improved school performance and student 
achievement, and a vastly improved working environment for teachers  and
principals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>America's public schools once provided citizens with a  common culture and a
sound basic education. In recent decades,  however, the public school system has
failed utterly to provide  Americans with these essentials.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>SAT scores have dropped nearly 60 points in the past three  decades  even
though the test has been &quot;dumbed down.&quot;  The  same answers in 1992 as
in 1960 score between 18 and 30 points  higher than three decades ago. Thus, the
real loss is somewhere  between 98 and 110 points.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#1">1</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In a classic example of denial, the Educational Testing Service  has
responded to this crisis by &quot;re-centering&quot; SAT scoring for  1995 and
beyond. To disguise the poor performances of American  students, all SAT scores
are now reported on a higher scale. The  test also has been renamed. No longer
the Scholastic Aptitude Test,  it is now the Scholastic Assessment Test: same
acronym, less utility.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>But trying to make the picture look better by altering SAT  scores fools
nobody. The school system is failing. In 1969, Congress  created the National
Assessment of Educational Progress (NAEP)  to survey student achievement
nationwide on a regular basis.  Over the years, these assessments have found
that: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     In 1986, almost 94 percent of high school seniors were
unable  to solve multi-step mathematical problems or use basic  algebra.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#2">2</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Almost 60 percent of high school seniors in 1988 were unable  to
understand and summarize relatively complicated reading  material.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#3">3</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     More than one-fourth of all 17-year-olds were unable to add, 
subtract, multiply, and divide using whole numbers, or to solve  one-step
mathematical problems.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#4">4</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     High school seniors age 17 in 1986 could answer correctly  only about
half the questions on the history and literature test; 68  percent did not know
when the Civil War occurred (26  percent thought it occurred before 1800), and
47 percent believed the  language of Karl Marx's dictum &quot;from each
according to his  ability, to each according to his need&quot; was from the U.S.
 Constitution.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#5">5</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Only 27 percent of American high school seniors in 1988  could read
and write a simple letter, and only 80 percent in 1992  could decipher a bus
schedule.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#6">6</A> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The latest results show that there has been little if any  improvement. The
1994 NAEP history assessment showed that more  than half of American high school
seniors lack a basic knowledge  of 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  U.S. history. The test, composed
of multiple choice and  essay questions, was given in early 1994 to a national
sample of  22,500 fourth, eighth, and 12th graders in both public and private 
schools. The results:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     Among 12th graders, only 43 percent attained at least the
 basic level; 11 percent were proficient; and 1 percent to 2 percent  advanced.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Among eighth graders, 61 percent attained basic; 14 percent, 
proficient; and 1 percent to 2 percent, advanced.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Among fourth graders, 64 percent attained basic; 17 percent, 
proficient; and 1 percent to 2 percent, advanced.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The information gets worse. A 1995 NAEP study revealed that  the best
writing students produce as part of their classroom work is  not very good.
Writing samples collected from a nationally  representative sample of more than
3,000 4th and 8th graders showed that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     Only 1 percent of 4th graders and 12 percent of 8th
graders  were able to write &quot;well developed&quot; stories. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     In informative writing, only 1 percent of 4th graders and 4  percent
of 8th graders could present &quot;developed&quot; discussions.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Fourth graders then were asked to read aloud and discuss  what they had
read. Only 55 percent were fluent in reading aloud a  portion of narrative text
that they had read silently twice before.  Only 13 percent consistently read
with appropriate phrasing and  expressiveness.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 1994 NAEP geography exam showed that only 22 percent  of 4th graders, 28
percent of 8th graders, and 27 percent of 12th  graders scored at the proficient
level.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#7">7
</A></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>States vary widely.</B> In its <I>Report Card on American  Education
1994</I>, a comprehensive state-by-state analysis of student  performance in all
50 states and the District of Columbia, the  American Legislative Exchange
Council (ALEC) found that:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     Nationwide, student performance did not improve 
significantly from 1992-1993 to 1993-1994. SAT scores remained  unchanged, 35
points below 1972-1973 levels; graduation rates were  unchanged as well, down
1.3 percent from 1980.  ACT<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#8">8</A> and
NAEP scores improved marginally.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Ten states dominated the nation on all measures of high 
student performance (SAT scores, ACT scores, NAEP fourth grade  and reading
scores, NAEP eighth grade mathematics scores, and  high school graduation
rates): Iowa, Kansas, Minnesota, Montana,  Nebraska, North Dakota, South Dakota,
Utah, Wisconsin, and  Wyoming (see Table 5).
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Spending at Record Levels</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While education performance has been mediocre at best,  education spending
is now at an all-time high. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For the 1994-1995 school year, total education spending in  the United
States was estimated to be $508.3 billion, up 178  percent from the 1980-1981
school year (see <a href="educ_t1.gif">Table 1</a>).This amounted  to about 7.5 percent of GDP for
1994-1995, almost double the  spending on national defense.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Total spending on public elementary and secondary schools for  the 1994-1995
school year was $283.9 billion, an increase of 173  percent from 1980-1981 in
nominal terms. From 1972 to 1992,  public school spending rose 490 percent in
nominal terms (see <a href="educ_t2.gif">Table 2</a>).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Overall, the federal government spent $35.2 billion in  constant 1994
dollars on education in 1994-1995, up from $29.7 billion  in 1980 (see <a href="educ_t3.gif">Table 3</a>).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Spending per pupil in the public schools has soared: $6,857  in 1994-1995,
up 150 percent from 1980-1981 in nominal terms  and 44 percent in 1994 dollars.
Since 1970, per-pupil spending  has risen 554 percent in nominal terms and 73
percent in  constant 1994 dollars (see Table TK).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>ALEC's report card clearly supports conservative arguments  that student
performance measures, compared with per-pupil  expenditures, average teacher
salaries, and other education spending  variables, indicate no direct or
systematic relationship between  spending and student performance. 
</P>
<P>None of the ten top-performing states in terms of student  achievement
ranked among the top ten in per-pupil education spending  in 1993-1994; most
spent less than the national average per pupil.  In addition, none of these
states ranked among the top ten in  average teacher salaries last year (eight
actually paid less than the  national average); nine held per-pupil spending
increases below the  national average during the last 11 years; and seven did so
during  the preceding 21 years as well.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As <a href="educ_t5.gif">Table 5</a> shows, Iowa scored first in SAT scores and tied  for 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 -->  first on the NAEP test, yet its
spending per pupil was below  the national average; Utah spent the least per
pupil, yet scored  second on the SAT and eighth on the NAEP test; and North 
Dakota ranked 36th in spending but tied for first on the NAEP test  and scored
fourth on the SAT. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>By contrast, New Jersey spent the highest amount per pupil  and scored 37th
on the SAT and 14th on the 1992 NAEP test; the  District of Columbia ranked
second in spending per pupil and  scored 49th on the SAT and 42nd out of 42
states on the NAEP test;  and ninth-ranked Rhode Island scored 43rd on the SAT
and 23rd  on the NAEP test.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     According to ALEC, report card, New Jersey spent
more per  student ($9,429) than any other state in the nation during the 
1993-1994 school year. New Jersey also held the same per-pupil  spending rank in
1992-1993 and still increased per-pupil spending  significantly more than the
national average. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Teacher salaries also increased nationwide last year, rising a
 modest 0.1 percent after inflation. Connecticut paid the highest  average
teacher salaries last year ($49,500); South Dakota, the  lowest ($25,199).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     By the year 2005, the total cost of public education will have
 increased substantially. Using Census Bureau population  projections, and
assuming per-pupil spending trends continue: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Total education spending will rise more than 47 percent 
(almost $125 billion in constant 1994 dollars), and per-pupil spending  will
increase almost 32 percent to $7,942. As a result, the  per-capita 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  education tax burden will rise by
one-third, and the typical  family of four will face an average annual education
tax increase  of $1,340.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>That there is no correlation between spending and performance  has been
demonstrated by a wide variety of studies, perhaps most  notably in the
exhaustive study of the performance of  America's schools for their landmark
1990 book, 
<I>Politics, Markets and America's Schools,</I> conducted by Brookings
Institution  Senior Fellows John Chubb and Terry Moe. The evidence showed 
clearly that increased spending and resources do not translate into  better
school or student performance. The relationship between  resources and
performance has been studied extensively by social  scientists, who agree that
financial resources are of less consequence  that other variables. Most
important is &quot;school climate,&quot; the extent  to which a school offers a
safe and disciplined learning  environment with staff and students motivated by
a shared commitment to  academic excellence. The performance problems of the
public  schools cannot be corrected solely by digging deeper into the  public
purse.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#9">9</A>  Many studies make this
point.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     Professor Eric Hanushek, Chairman of the
Economics  Department at the University of Rochester, reviewed 187 studies 
which showed no statistically significant correlation between  education
spending and performance.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#10">10</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In a study for The Heritage Foundation, Douglas Munro found 
no positive correlation between state education spending per  pupil and student
performance on the 1990 NAEP national  mathematics test.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#11">11</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>As Chubb and Moe conclude:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>     [R]esearchers have generally been unable to establish a 
statistically significant relationship between student  achievement and any of
the school characteristics that are often  thought important: teacher-pupil
ratios, teacher education,  teacher salaries, and per pupil expenditures. This
should come as  no great surprise. Over the last two decades, as school 
performance has deteriorated and stagnated, per-pupil spending  in schools has
increased nearly 100 percent after inflation,  class sizes have shrunk more than
20 percent, and most  teachers have acquired master's degrees.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#12">12</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>International Comparisons
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>On the home front, there is some modest good news. Black  test scores have
made small gains, and women's have as well.  More students are taking more
demanding courses. The number of  them taking advanced placement courses and
tests continues to rise,  as does the number of higher scores. But these are
just a few  bright spots in a gloomy picture. The bottom line for conservative 
candidates is that all American children could be doing  significantly better,
as indeed all must if we are to have confidence in the  future. Academic
performance in America is not world-class,  and offers no promise of becoming
world-class by the year 2000  except in a few isolated schools and districts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The reasons for this huge discrepancy between America's  schools and our
international competitors are not hard to fathom.  American public schools are
not designed to succeed. Pony Express  institu
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 -->  tions in the electronic age, they
are hopelessly out of date.  The issue is not money (see <a href="educ_2.gif"
>chart</a>), but standards,
organization,  and accountability. Too little is expected of American students;
as  a consequence, they give too little. There are few rewards for  success and
fewer penalties for failure. A system designed and  run without incentives and
rewards ineluctably panders to the  lowest common denominator, as American
education has done.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Where Teachers Send Their Children to School</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Public school teachers are sending their own children to  private schools
rather than allow them to become lost in a public  school system in disarray.
This was reported in a May 1995 study by  The Heritage Foundation's <a href="/heritage/staff/doyle.html">Denis Doyle</a>,
prepared under the  auspices of the Indiana-based Hudson Institute and published
and  distributed by the Washington-based Center for Education  Reform.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#13">13</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This study, drawn from the 5 percent household sample of  the 1990 Census,
shows that, taken together, public and private  school teachers nationwide are
only slightly more likely than the  general public to choose private schools
(17.1 percent to 13.1 percent).  In America's most troubled cities, however, the
results are quite  different:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In troubled cities, public school teachers are two to three  times more
likely than the general public to use private schools. For  example, in
Washington, D.C., 25.7 percent of public school  teachers who make less than
$35,000 send their children to private  school. This is more than double the
national average; among  public school teachers nationwide, 11.9 percent enroll
some or all of  their children in private school. The trend continues in cities
like  Boston 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->  (24.4 percent), New York (21.4
percent), Miami (35.4  percent), and Los Angeles (18.9 percent). 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In other words, &quot;in our nation's cities, where the schools are 
arguably the worst, a large number of teachers abandon the  institutions in
which they work and enroll their offspring in private schools.&quot;   This
includes teachers of all races.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Black public school teachers use private schools more than  white public
school teachers (12.9 percent to 11.9 percent), and  Hispanic public school
teachers use private schools more than  non-Hispanic public school teachers
(16.5 percent to 11.9 percent).  Meanwhile, white parents are somewhat more
likely than nonwhite parents  to send their children to a private school. In the
United States as  a whole, 13.1 percent of all parents, 14.2 percent of white 
parents, 8.1 percent of black parents, and 10.8 percent of parents of  other
races send their children to private schools. Some 13.4 percent  of Hispanic
parents send their children to private school, compared  to 10.1 percent of all
non-Hispanic parents.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Overall, then, black public school teachers are almost as likely  as the
public at large to use private schools (12.9 percent to 13.1  percent). This
means that &quot;black teachers who can afford a  choice exercise it: they are
50 percent more likely than black parents  in general to enroll their children
in private school. This might  explain the high support for publicly funded
school choice  programs among minorities  they are often in the worst school
districts  and are more inclined to put their children in private schools when 
they can afford it.&quot;  Across the United States, &quot;teachers  public  and
private, white and black, Hispanic and non-Hispanic, low  income, middle income,
and high income  know how to address  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 -->  nation's education crisis: they
vote with their feet and their  pocket books. They choose private schools for
their children when  they think it serves their interests best.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>How Teacher Unions Obstruct Reform </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The American Federation of Teachers (AFT) and the larger  National Education
Association (NEA) have become the  bane<U> </U>of school reformers. They are
big and well funded, and they have  a major presence in Washington and most
state capitals.  Teachers are, in fact, the most heavily unionized segment of
the  American work force, and the NEA is particularly opposed to serious 
education reform. But teachers are not necessarily synonymous  with their
unions. They vote for Republicans as well as Democrats  and are concerned with
many of the same issues that concern  reformers. The tide could begin to turn. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>One sign that teachers recognize the need for reform, as  noted above and in
the following table, is the extent to which they  enroll their own children in
private schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Another encouraging sign is the willingness of AFT  President Albert Shanker
to champion high academic standards and  school discipline.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#14">14</A>  At the same time, however,
Shanker's opposition  to innovations such as school choice remains implacable.
The  education establishment fears that public schools as we know them  will
disappear, but this is all the more reason to adopt a more  innovative approach
to public education. This fear of change is  narrow and self-serving. Preferring
the known to the unknown, the  education establishment reveals its limited
vision and how little it  actually cares about the welfare of children.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Federal Takeover</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The attempted federal takeover of American education,  launched with fanfare
and good will during the Great Society 30 years  ago, has been revealed for what
it is: a prolonged and serious  mistake. It is now abundantly clear that
Washington both  over-promised and overreached. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Programs intended to improve the education of the poor and  dispossessed
have borne bitter fruit, emerging by and large as  self-serving employment
programs for educators. Student test  scores have remained largely static, and
the promise of public  education as a way out of the mire of social pathology
has not  materialized. Instead, inner-city public schools themselves have become
 trapped in the pathology of the inner city. Almost without exception,  the only
schools which have escaped, and whose students have  done well, are private
denominational schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The dismal state of American education is deeply troubling  to those who
have examined it most closely. As Chubb and  Moe write:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>     Whether the criticisms have come from average  citizens,
business leaders, public officials, or educators  themselves, they have had a
common thrust: the schools are failing  in their core academic mission,
particularly in the more  rigorous areas of study  math, science, foreign
languages  so  crucial to a future of sophisticated technology and international
 competition. America's children are not learning enough, they  are not learning
the right things, and, most debilitating of all,  they 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 -->  are not learning how to learn.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#15">15</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The state of American public education is summarized bluntly  by former
Education Secretary William Bennett:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>     The most reliable indicators of student performance  
Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) scores, American College  Test (ACT) scores, the
National Assessment of  Educational Progress (NAEP) scores and graduation rates 
confirm  the fact that we have suffered a severe decline in education.  Ten
years ago, the landmark education report, <U>A Nation At  Risk</U>, declared
that &quot;we have, in effect, been committing an act  of unthinking, unilateral
educational disarmament.&quot;   Despite having spent almost $2 trillion on
elementary and  secondary education since then, things have not gotten
appreciably  better. In fact, some test scores (verbal SAT scores, for  example)
are <U>lower</U> than they were in  1983.16
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Violence in America's Schools</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Violence in America's schools has reached epidemic proportions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     &quot;Twenty percent of high school students now
carry a  firearm, knife, razor, club or some other weapon on a regular  basis.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#17">17</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     According to the National League of Cities, school violence 
during 1994 resulted in student death and injury in 41 percent of  American
cities with a population of 100,000 or  more.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#18">18</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     &quot;In 1995, 48% of high school seniors had used some form
of  illegal drug at least once, up almost 3 percentage points from  1994.
Marijuana use among eighth-graders has nearly doubled  since 1991, with 20
percent saying they have used it at least once,  up from 17 percent only a year
earlier.&quot;<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#19">19</A>  Smoking among
eighth  and tenth graders has increased one-third since 1991 and has risen 
one-fifth among high school seniors since 1992. Alcohol use  remains the most
popular drug among teenagers, with nearly 81  percent reporting that they had
tried drinking alcohol at some point in  their lives.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#20">20</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Approximately 900 teachers throughout the nation are 
threatened with bodily harm, and nearly 40 teachers are physically  attacked,
each hour of the school day. Some 160,000 students miss  school daily because of
intimidation or fear of bodily  harm.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#21">21</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     A 1993 <I>USA Weekend</I> survey on school disruption
revealed  that nearly 40 percent of students nationwide think schools are 
unsafe.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#22">22</A>  They are right to think
so. The survey reported that  2,000 students were physically attacked each hour
of the school day;  one in five carried a weapon to school daily; nearly half of
those in  the survey said they avoided school restrooms out of fear; and a  full
63 percent said they would learn more if they felt  safer.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#23">23</A>  Some will never learn; at least
30 violent deaths occurred in the  schools in the past academic year.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#24">24</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Too many of America's public school teachers must perform  under combat
conditions.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#25">25</A>  Worse, teachers too
often receive little  support from local boards of education or school
administrators.  Yet, despite the barrage of disrespectful behavior on the part
of  unruly students and the lack of action from school authorities,  America's 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 -->  classroom teachers more often
than not make heroic efforts to  educate America's youth.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Surrender by Teachers and Administrators. Frustrated parents  frequently ask
whether there is anything the school system can do  to help with their runaway
teen, their drug-dealing son, or  their daughter who has been truant and is
thought to be working as  a prostitute in a major city. To be sure, the
wholesale use of  profanity and general disrespect in many classrooms is of
grave  concern to teachers and administrators. But too often, they are driven 
to ignore or even tolerate disruption and abuse that years ago, in  a more
ordered, civilized society, would have been considered  deviant and
unacceptable. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Too many teachers, for example, lose valuable time allotted  for instruction
because of the number of troubled youngsters in  the class. Likewise, many
teachers and administrators allow  aggressive student confrontations to develop
without immediately  correcting students. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     A 1993 study for the National School Boards
Association  noted the inability of a growing number of students to communicate 
with one another when an argument arises. &quot;Mouthing off&quot;  quickly
turns uglier, too frequently resulting in physical violence,  according to this
survey of 1,100 administrators.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#26">26</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Commenting on one high school, the Maryland State  Teachers
Association has stated that the discipline situation is &quot;far  worse than
has been reported, and it is getting worse daily.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In a Maryland school, the department chairperson stated that  &quot;an

<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 -->  attempt has been made to put a
positive spin on the problem  of severely disruptive students by calling them
merely  misguided youth. Unfortunately, we are not talking about students who 
chew gum in class or call out instead of raising their hands or even  students
who cut class occasionally.&quot;  The &quot;misguided youth&quot; at  this
school had set two students' hair on fire; squirted a fire  extinguisher at a
teacher; thrown batteries, pennies, chalk, books,  or anything else at hand at
staff members; savagely assaulted  other students; brought guns and drugs to
school; and verbally  assaulted many, if not most, of the teachers in the
building. They had  vandalized the building, as well as property in the
surrounding  neighborhood. They roamed the building all day long in packs of
five  to 20 with seeming impunity. Good students were trying to  transfer, while
good teachers wanted to retire or resign. The sad thing  is that this school is
probably not as bad as some  others.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#27">27</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>If local and state officials really wish to improve the education  of our
students, they can begin by improving the conditions  under which too many
American public school teachers are asked  to work and teach. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Why Vouchers Are Needed</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The main difficulty in addressing the sorry state of  America's schools lies
in the fact that those in charge have a vested interest  in resisting change.
The efforts of those most concerned about  falling test scores  usually parents,
but many teachers as well   usually meet with a discouraging combination of
bureaucratic lethargy  and outright resistance. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For this reason, the first order of business for reformers must be  to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->  wrest enough control from the
bureaucracy to effect  serious change. Several promising policy solutions have
been put  forward to accomplish this. One of the best is the concept of school 
choice, which would end the &quot;one size fits all&quot; approach to the public
 education system by opening up options for students to attend  higher-quality
private schools. The best way to make private  schools more accessible to the
parents of children currently enrolled  in public schools is also the simplest:
through government vouchers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>School choice vouchers are transfer payments from the  government to
families of school-age children which permit these  children to attend the
school of their choice, whether public or  private, secular or religious. The
practice is widely followed in the  developed democracies and is spreading
rapidly in the former Iron  Curtain countries. America is, in fact, the only
developed nation  that denies its children this form of assistance to help them
attend  non-public and denominational schools. It may well be that the  last
truly deprived minority in the United States is made up of  poor children whose
families prefer a religious education but  cannot afford to pay for it out of
pocket.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#28">28</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Numerous opinion polls show broad public support for  school choice,
especially among inner-city minorities and the poor,  who suffer the worst
schools under the current system with no  feasible alternatives. School choice
offers conservative candidates a  powerful opportunity to attract strong support
from this traditionally  liberal constituency.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The opposition, by contrast, comes from the education and  union
bureaucracies  the only people who gain from the current  monopoly. School
choice is a threat to them because it would  give 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  parents and teachers the power
and control enjoyed for decades  by a professional managerial elite increasingly
out of touch with  the communities they are supposed to be serving.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Role of Charter Schools</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Two other promising innovations are the charter school and a  related idea,
private contracting for school services. Charter  schools are public
institutions in terms of mission and funding, but are  run autonomously by the
signatories of a charter. They can be run  by an association of parents,
teachers, business leaders, or any  combination of these. While the charter
school movement is both  new and small, varying significantly from state to
state, the idea  is promising. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The basic concept of charter schools is simple: &quot;Allow a group  of
teachers or other would be educators to apply for permission  to open a school.
Give them dollar for dollar what a public  school gets for each student but
without any strings attached. Free  them from the regulations that cripple
learning and stifle innovation  at so many public schools.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#29">29</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In the four years since the first charter schools opened their  doors in
Minnesota, 18 other states have passed charter laws in  various forms, and 234
of these schools are up and running around  the country.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#30">30</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Three States with Different Charter School  Concepts</B><A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#31">31</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>ARIZONA:</B> No law perfectly embodies the charter concept,  but
Arizona's comes closest. Lawmakers revised the law in 1995. 
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Cap:</B>  None. </P>
<P><B>Schools open:</B> 47. </P>
<P><B>Approval:</B> Any public body, private  person, or private organization
may organize a school. A charter  may be sponsored by a local school board, the
state board of  education, or the state board for charter schools.</P>
<P><B>State/local control:</B> All  charter schools are exempt from state laws
except those  regarding health, safety, civil rights, insurance, and children
with  disabilities or special needs. Local districts have no legal authority 
over schools sponsored by the state board of education or the  state board for
charter schools.</P>
<P><B>Private school eligibility:</B> Yes, if  the school is nonsectarian, but
it must become a public school and  no longer accept tuition.</P>
<P><B>Hiring:</B> Schools are not required to hire  certified teachers.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>MINNESOTA:</B> The state that pioneered the charter concept  revised its
law to strengthen it in 1993 and 1995. </P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Cap:</B> Increased  to 40 schools in 1995 after being set
originally at eight and later at  12 schools. </P>
<P><B>Schools open:</B> 17. </P>
<P><B>Approval:</B> Only licensed teachers  can operate a school. Charters
must first be approved by a local  school board, community college, state
university, or technical  college, with the state board of education granting
final approval. Such  an approval process is more limiting than Arizona's, but
in 1993,  lawmakers amended the original law so that charter applicants 
rejected by the local school board can appeal to the state board  if two members
of the local board voted to approve the  charter.</P>
<P><B>State/local control:</B> Schools are exempt from state laws and local 
district policies except those regarding health, safety, civil rights, and 
children with disabilities or special needs. They also have  complete control of
the money they receive from the state.</P>
<P><B>Private  school eligibility:</B> Yes, if the school is nonsectarian, but
it must become  a public school and no longer accept tuition.</P>
<P><B>Hiring:</B> Schools  must hire only certified teachers.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>GEORGIA:</B> Charter advocates say the Georgia law  encourages
site-based management of schools but has little to do with  the charter school
concept. It is one of the toughest states in which  to start a school.</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Cap:</B> None.</P>
<P><B>Schools open:</B> 3.</P>
<P><B>Approval:</B> Schools  can be organized only by Georgia public school
staff or faculty. For  an existing public school to become a charter school,
two-thirds  of the faculty and staff must agree. Schools must be approved by 
the local school board and the state board of education.</P>
<P><B>State/local control:</B> All schools remain under the authority of the
local  school board.</P>
<P><B>Private school eligibility:</B> No.</P>
<P><B>Hiring:</B> Schools may hire  non-certified teachers if they get a
waiver from the district and state.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The most thoroughly developed example is Yvonne Chan's  Next Century
Learning Center in Los Angeles, and the most  promising state legislation for
Charter Schools is Arizona's which is  wide-ranging and flexible. In most
jurisdictions, however,  charter schools are poorly developed and kept on a
short leash. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The education establishment  notably the National  Education Association and
various school board associations at the state  and national levels  give lip
service to charter schools but offer  no real support. The reason: Charter
schools are a very real threat  to the status quo. Once in place, they could
revolutionize  American education. They combine the best aspects of a
functioning  public school system  public support, public access and
accountability   with much of the flexibility of private schools. They are an 
important and useful first step to freeing teachers and parents.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Contract Management.</B> Still in its infancy as a way of  operating
schools or school districts, contract management of various  aspects 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 -->  of education is a
long-established practice. School cafeterias,  busing, business services,
textbook acquisition, purchase of  supplies and materials, janitorial services,
and the like have been  turned over to private contractors and run efficiently
in many districts  for many years. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>What remains is to begin trying the concept in curriculum  areas such as
reading, math, and foreign languages, as well as in  running whole schools or
school districts. There is no conceptual barrier  to contract management; it is
used in almost all other areas of  government services, from national park
concessions to military  training.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The idea behind contract management is simple: Pay an  independent
contractor to perform an assigned task and devise  measures that will determine
whether that task has been performed  successfully. Interestingly, one of the
most difficult tasks school  districts face in contract management is &quot;specifying&quot;
the terms of the  contract; since many schools do not have a clear sense of 
mission, they find it very difficult to specify what they want to  accomplish in
the language of a contract. The exercise, however, is useful,  and education
establishment opposition to such a straightforward  idea is both
anti-intellectual and inflammatory. The issue is subject  to analysis and
validation, and should be welcomed as another way  to improve education
performance.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Business Involvement in Education</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Business leaders, teachers, and superintendents in May 1995  were asked a
variety of questions by the National Alliance of  Business and by Scholastic,
Inc., the publisher of 
<CITE><U>Scholastic Magazine</U></CITE>, re
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 24 -->  garding the educational
preparation of American students.  The results show that superintendents are
very pleased with the  job they are doing, while their clients, the business
leaders, are  highly dissatisfied. Those answering &quot;yes&quot;:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     &quot;Do you think our nation's public schools
are doing a good  job preparing students for the world of work?&quot;  Business,
4  percent; superintendents, 68 percent; teachers, 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     &quot;Do you think your local public schools do a good job of 
preparing students for the world of work?&quot;  Business, 16 percent; 
superintendents, 76 percent; teachers, 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     &quot;Do you think business should have input into what
students  are taught?&quot;  All groups, 96 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     &quot;Do you think we should have clear academic standards for
 what students should know and be able to do?&quot;  Business and  teachers, 92
percent; superintendents, 96 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     &quot;Do you feel that public education is improving in the 
United States?&quot;  Business, 12 percent; superintendents, 88 percent; 
teachers, 52 percent.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Business leaders have good reason to be concerned.  Employers incur huge
costs because of poor education.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     An insurance clerk for one company authorized paying
$2,200  on a $22 bill because she did not understand decimals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     A steel mill employee ordered $1 million worth of the wrong  parts 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->  because he could not understand
written instructions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     An electronics firm spends an average of $250 per employee  to train
workers in quality control techniques while its Japanese  competitor spends only
50 cents per employee on such training.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     A telephone company found that 86 percent of its 22,900  applicants
did not have entry-level proficiency in English and  problem solving.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Citicorp Savings Bank of Illinois, a subsidiary of Citibank of  New
York, rejects 840 of every 1,000 applicants for entry-level  teller and clerical
positions because they cannot complete the  application forms.
</P>
<P>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Businesses spend over $30 billion per year on employee  training and
retraining, much of it made necessary by the failure of  the public schools.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#32">32</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Because business is a major stockholder in education quality, it  is time
business began to demand of schools what it demands of  itself: high standards,
real accountability, rewards for success,  and penalties for failure. Business
also can play a critical role in  helping schools set priorities, identify
measurement tools,  improve communication with and between schools and the
larger  community, and help develop performance measures that will  rationalize
pay for teachers and administrators. Perhaps most important of  all, business
leaders can help school boards behave in a more  businesslike fashion. In
particular, business can help school boards  end &quot;micro-management&quot;
and support candidates for school  boards who are both responsible and
effective. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>State Reforms in 1995</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 1995 legislative session once again brought school choice  to the
forefront of the education debate at the state level. State  legislatures
debated numerous voucher and charter school bills over  the 1995 session, and
several states have passed or improved  their charter school laws. In two
states, Ohio and Wisconsin,  first-in-the-nation school choice programs were put
into  place.<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#33">33</A>  Several other
states debated the issues and some proposals cleared the  relevant committees. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The main changes enacted into law:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Charter Schools.</B> Both chambers of the Florida legislature  passed
charter school bills in 1995. Legislators are consolidating the  bills, and
Governor Lawton Chiles is expected to sign. The  Louisiana Senate passed a
charter school bill that is now being considered  in the House. 
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>
</P>
<P>Mississippi, Oregon, and Connecticut also considered  charter school
legislation. In Oregon, the House narrowly defeated a  charter school bill by a
vote of 31-29. The bill has been sent to  the Legislative Rules Committee, where
it could be amended and  returned to the full House for another vote in 1996.
Connecticut  is considering many education reforms, including both a  voucher
proposal and charter schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Both Arizona and Massachusetts have approved charter  school applications
for next year. Arizona education officials have  approved 47 charter schools.
Meanwhile, 15 charter schools  will 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 -->  open in 1996 in Massachusetts.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Voucher Update.</B> According to Marquette University's Blum  Center for
Parental Freedom in Education, choice and voucher  initiatives were pursued in
the following states during 1995.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*    Ohio.</B> Governor George Voinovich in June signed
into law a  two-year budget package creating a $5.25 million pilot voucher 
program in Cleveland, to become effective in September 1996.  With his
signature, Governor Voinovich enabled Ohio to become  the first state in the
nation to complete the enactment of school  choice that includes religious
schools. The proposal included in the  budget package was approved by the
House-Senate Conference  Committee on June 23, 1995, and will allow parents of
2,000  Cleveland students to redeem vouchers at private or religious schools. 
With this new legislation, Cleveland becomes only the second city in  the
country (the first being Milwaukee) to allow private school choice.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Wisconsin.</B> In June, Wisconsin's legislature passed genuine 
school choice legislation, which, along with the rest of Governor  Tommy
Thompson's budget proposal, was signed into law on July  25, 1995. The
legislation called for the expansion of the  Milwaukee Parental Choice Program
to include religiously based  schools (MPCP currently allows students to attend
non-sectarian  private schools in Milwaukee).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Governor Thompson's earliest version of the choice proposal  had set the
voucher amount at $3,300 per pupil and raised the  number of eligible students
to 3,500 in the fall of 1996 and 5,500 in  the next year, after which the
enrollment limitation would have  been eliminated. Before the package was
approved by the Joint  Finance 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 28 -->  Committee, Representative Annette
&quot;Polly&quot; Williams, the  original sponsor of MPCP, called for a larger
expansion proposal  which increased enrollment to 7,000 in the fall of 1996,
after which  it would be limited to 15,000. This expanded proposal was  approved
by the Senate on June 29 after having been approved by the  State Assembly on
June 21.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>However, on August 25, the Wisconsin State Supreme Court  issued an
injunction halting the expansion of the Milwaukee  Parental Choice Program to
include religious schools. This action  left more than 2,300 children stranded
after having already signed  up for classes in the religious schools of their
parents'choice. In  an astonishing display of community support, private funds
have  been raised to offset the loss of public funding. Oral arguments  have
been set for February 27, 1996, and a final decision is not  expected from the
Wisconsin Supreme Court until spring. According to  the Landmark Legal
Foundation of Kansas City, Missouri, &quot;the  Milwaukee school-choice
litigation will ultimately result in a  major U.S. Supreme Court decision
allowing school-choice  programs that include religious programs.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Massachusetts.</B> In November, Governor William Weld  announced a
statewide program to provide tuition vouchers to  low-income families who wish
to send their children to religious as well  as non-sectarian private schools.
According to a summary of  Governor Weld's proposal, his plan would make
vouchers available  at public and non-sectarian private schools during the first
phase  of reform. During the second phase, an amendment to the  Massachusetts
Constitution would be proposed to expand the program  to include religious
schools. Governor Weld planned to introduce  the voucher program in the
Massachusetts House early in 1996.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 29 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Minnesota.</B> Previously only a supporter of public school 
choice, Governor Arne Carlson in July announced his intention to  introduce in
1996 a pilot program for genuine school choice in  Minneapolis, St. Paul, and
Brooklyn Center, a Twin Cities suburb.  Recently, Carlson's staff revealed that
the proposal would likely  offer vouchers worth approximately $500 to $3,000, to
be given on  a sliding scale according to income. A family of four  earning
$40,000 could still qualify for the vouchers. Carlson insists  a voucher program
will create more competition, which in turn  will spawn excellence.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     New Jersey.</B> Governor Christine Todd Whitman delayed until 
1996 the introduction of a school choice proposal, originally to be  introduced
at the end of 1995, and has appointed a panel to  examine school choice in the
wake of promised legal challenges from  the New Jersey Education Association, a
powerful coalition of  groups opposing vouchers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Meanwhile, Jersey City Mayor Bret Schundler, a staunch  advocate of school
choice, has announced the introduction of a  privately funded voucher program
for the city to begin in January 1996.  The idea initially gained massive
financial backing from  Pepsi-Cola and the Bodman Foundation, but Pepsi-Cola
recently withdrew  its support in the wake of local teachers' union opposition
and talk  of product boycotts.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION</B>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 30 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>President Clinton promised to do something to help improve  the education of
America's children. While his rhetoric has been  appealing, however, he has
failed to keep his promise. Instead  of &quot;revolutionizing, revitalizing and
reforming&quot; America's  schools, he actually has slowed the process of
change. While creating  new government bureaucracies, increasing federal
regulations,  and boosting the rate of spending at the federal level, the 
Administration also has resisted real efforts to reform America's  education
system. The President has chosen to ignore academic &quot;outputs&quot;   real
results  and has focused instead on spending more  taxpayer dollars on &quot;inputs.&quot;
 The Administration also has seriously  undermined the relationship of students
and their families to the  education process.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Federal Takeover of School Districts (Goals 2000).</B> The  Goals
2000 legislation, enacted in 1994 as President Clinton's most  important
education program, has been a failure. Instead of  &quot;revolutionizing,
revitalizing and reforming&quot; America's schools as  President Clinton
promised, Goals 2000 has proved a barrier  to change.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#34">34</A>  It has created new government
bureaucracy and  boosted federal spending. Worse still, it threatens to
undermine progress  to improve American education performance by encouraging 
schools to ignore real results and focus instead on obtaining federal  dollars
by showing Washington that more money is being spent on  &quot;inputs.&quot; 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Continued taxpayer funding for Goals 2000 will only  strengthen the federal
government's power to control local reform efforts  and hamper grassroots
reform. It is time for Congress to terminate  the program and divert the money
to real reform.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 31 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Goals 2000 has failed America's schools in two important ways:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Building Bureaucracies.</B> Under Goals 2000, three new  government
bureaucracies would have been created: the National  Education Goals Panel, the
National Education Standards and  Improvement Council (NESIC), and the National
Skills Board. While  NESIC will not be empaneled, the philosophy behind these 
bureaucracies continues the command-and-control approach that keeps control  of
schools in the hands of education bureaucrats rather than  parents, teachers,
and students.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Federalizing Education.</B> While Goals 2000 pays lip service to  local
control, it came dangerously close to mandating a  watered-down national
curriculum designed in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The federal government's preliminary foray into identifying  national
history standards  a well-meaning attempt by  then-National Endowment for the
Humanities Chairman Lynne Cheney  to make educators teach real history again 
backfired last year  when the committee assigned to formulate them unveiled
standards  that were rife with political correctness. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The incident reveals one of the inherent dangers in the Goals  2000
approach. Had its members been appointed, NESIC would  have become a de facto
national school board whose 19 members  could have imposed a standard curriculum
of politically correct  revisionism on the entire nation. This central authority
would have  approved or disapproved all state-developed plans to meet goals  set
by the Education Goals Panel, another bureaucracy created  under Goals 2000.
Such attempts to federalize state and local  education discourage real
innovation and inhibit the most important  school 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 32 -->  reform initiative of the decade,
the movement toward  privatization and school choice.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The states, meanwhile, on their own initiative already have  begun to reject
federal interference in schooling. In particular,  outcomes based education, a
favorite idea of the education  establishment, has offended and alienated
thoughtful teachers and parents  across the country and has mobilized opposition
to the federal role.  Four states  Montana, New Hampshire, Virginia, and Alabama
  have turned down or returned Goals 2000 funding, refusing to  permit more
federal intrusion.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Another Middle-Class Subsidy:</B> AmeriCorps. Hailed by the 
Administration as an innovative effort to expand education  opportunity through
volunteerism, AmeriCorps, President Clinton's  national service program, has
evolved into a big-government  pork barrel. Although supporters maintain
AmeriCorps  &quot;encourages Americans to do volunteer work, helps people go to
college  and disperses decision-making power from Washington to  the states,&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#35">35</A> the rhetoric contrasts sharply
with reality. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The AmeriCorps program does little to help American  families pay for
college, destroys the spirit of volunteerism, removes  participants from local
communities where they are needed most  and uses them to enlarge the federal
bureaucracy, and  improperly funds partisan political activities. Most
important,  AmeriCorps costs the taxpayers too much.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>An August 1995 General Accounting Office report found  that AmeriCorps costs
$26,654 per participant to run, or more than  40 percent more than the
Administration's most recent  estimates. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 33 -->  Some 93 percent of the funding
for the program comes out of  taxpayers' pockets.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1993-1994, AmeriCorps employed about 20,000  &quot;volunteers&quot;
described as &quot;working all over America, helping people   person to person.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#36">36</A>  In reality, a significant number
of these highly  paid &quot;volunteers&quot; are working in federal or state
bureaucracies,  government-funded programs, or political action organizations.
Of  the 20,000 &quot;volunteers&quot; currently participating in the program, 
2,053 are working in federal bureaucracies on programs funded by  the federal
government. <a href="educ_t8.gif">Table 8</a> presents a breakdown of  AmeriCorps participation within the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Student Loans.</B> While the Clinton Administration has portrayed  its
direct lending program for college students as essential to the  education
future of young Americans, the evidence suggests  otherwise. The program appears
to be bad for taxpayers, bad for  students, and bad for schools. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The vast bulk of capital for student loans today is provided  through
private institutions. But under the direct lending plan, the  federal government
borrows the money needed to provide capital for  the loans. This would require
the federal government to borrow  an additional $20 billion-$25 billion each
year. According to  Representative Ernest Istook (R-OK), a complete shift to
direct  loans could add as much as $348 billion to the national debt by the 
year 2014. The U.S. Department of Education is expanding to  handle the new
program, hiring 600 new employees to administer it  and anticipating need for
another 20,000 contract employees by  the time the program is fully operational.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 34 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are other worries about the direct lending program.  Currently, some
75 percent of all available college financial aid  comes from the federal
government. If the government takes  complete control of the loan program,
colleges and universities in effect  will become dependent on a single lender to
support their students.  The Education Department's power to control loan
revenue, along  with its expanded regulatory authority and enforcement power, 
will give the government vast influence over post-secondary  education. Such
financial power could enable the federal government to  influence or force
curriculum changes, or to mandate such things  as politically correct &quot;diversity
standards.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There is little support for a government takeover of the  guaranteed lending
program. The solution is not to nationalize  the multibillion-dollar student
loan program. That would mean  new costs and bureaucracy. Moreover, Americans
believe strongly  that student loans should continue to be provided through
private  financial institutions, not the federal government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE 104TH CONGRESS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The actions taken so far by the 104th Congress have  produced mixed results.
For the first time in 40 years, there was hope  for serious change in America's
education system. The Contract  With America, however, included little
discussion of education  reform or of countering President Clinton's hindering
of legislative  actions. After the first legislative year of the Republican 
majority, despite attempts to introduce far reaching reforms, liberal 
strangleholds and repeated filibusters have caused the 104th Congress  to fall
far short of implementing any serious reform. At the  same 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 35 -->  time, however, conservative
actions within Congress have  helped make education one of the key issues in
1996.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reforming schools in the Nation's  Capital.</B> At the request of House
Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-GA), the Task Force on  D.C. Schools and Representative
Steve Gunderson (R-WI) developed  a plan that would have laid the foundation for
serious reform in  the District of Columbia public school system. Fundamental to
 these reforms was a scholarship proposal that would have put the  federal
government on record as supporting the concept of choice.  The proposal was
added as an amendment to the D.C. FY 1996  appropriations bill in the House.
Unfortunately, due to intense  objections by Democrats and liberal Republicans
in the  House-Senate Conference Committee, the entire set of education reforms 
remains in limbo as both sides refuse to budge.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Gunderson amendment authorized the establishment of  independent public
charter schools which would have used  existing D.C. public and private schools
as well as new schools  created with the help of the universities within the
District. It also  would have authorized many federal institutions within D.C., 
including the National Science Foundation, NASA, the Library of  Congress, and
the Smithsonian Institution, to help establish public  charter schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Gunderson legislation would have given scholarships of up  to $3,000 for
students whose family incomes were at or below  the poverty level and up to
$1,500 for students whose family  incomes were not more than 185 percent above
the poverty level.  These scholarships would have allowed low-income D.C.
families to  escape the failing D.C. public schools by giving them the 
resources 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 36 -->  needed to send their children to
any private, independent,  religious or non-religious school located in the
District of Columbia or  the surrounding counties of Northern Virginia and
Maryland.  They would have covered the cost of fees and other expenses for 
tutoring and instructional services after school hours and the costs  of
transportation for a student enrolled in a District of Columbia  public school,
public charter school, or private school participating  in the tuition
scholarship program. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Also included in the legislation was language to expand local  literacy
programs for the District from two programs to 20 in  the third year of the
initiative. These programs are instrumental  in helping to build reading skills
for children and their parents.  The legislation also would have helped
establish a panel to develop  a high expectations, academically challenging
curriculum and  assessment system for the D.C. school system.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Title I.</B> For more than 30 years, since 1965, Washington
has  spent over $90.5 billion on the Title I program, which still cannot  show
any long-term academic gains for children, even after being  &quot;reformed&quot;
five times. The House offered to cut funding for this  remedial education
program by $1.1 billion, from its current level  of $6.6 billion to $5.554
billion. The President is seeking $7  billion. Funding for the program is tied
to the Departments of  Labor, Health and Human Services, and Education
appropriations  bill, which passed the House but had not been brought to the
floor  of the Senate for a vote by the end of the 1995 session because  of
opposition by Senate Democrats.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Head Start.</B> While it is clear from several studies that any  success
for disadvantaged preschoolers gained through the early stages  of 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 37 -->  Head Start is eroded by the time
the children reach the  primary grades, over the past 30 years Washington has
spent over  $31.2 billion on the program. Unfortunately, Congress has decided 
to continue its funding. The House passed a $3.39 billion grant  for preschool
health and education for FY 1996, which returns  Head Start funding to slightly
more than was allocated in 1994.  Again, the Senate has yet to take up the
appropriations for the  program. President Clinton is seeking an increase in
program funding  in order to extend services to 50,000 or more children by the 
year 2002.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Student Loans.</B> House and Senate Republicans attempted
to kill  the President's bureaucratic and bloated direct lending program.  But
after negotiations with the White House, Congress agreed to a  pilot program
with a 10 percent cap for colleges and  universities involved. The agreement
includes:
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     $4.9 billion in savings in the Guaranteed Student Loan
program,  to be effected by increasing the risk on the loan defaults that  banks
carry and imposing increased costs on private lenders and  guaranty agencies,
none of which may be passed onto students, parents,  or schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Increasing the loan volume from $25 billion to $36 billion in  the
year 2002, an increase of nearly 50 percent, allowing the  number of loans to
rise from 6.6 million to 7.1 million by 1996.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     For all students, a guarantee that federal interest subsidies on 
student loans remain intact, including during the six-month  grace period
following graduation.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 38 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     For all qualified students, a guarantee that interest repaid on a 
student loan will be tax deductible.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     For all parents, a guarantee that the interest rate on parent  loans
remains the same. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     No denial of access to a student loan from capping the direct  lending
program.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Safe and Drug-free Schools.</B> The House leadership has
acted to  cut this program, a &quot;black hole&quot; in federal funding, by more
than  half, from $441 million to $200 million. The rationale is that  the
program's funds are spread too thin, with some districts  getting only a few
hundred dollars. This program has shown no  effectiveness in reducing drug usage
in high schools, and there have  been no specific performance-based evaluations
of it since its  inception. Furthermore, a program evaluation report has shown
that  training sessions are &quot;more likely to focus on providing information 
about the use of various drugs than teaching resistance and  decision-making
skills.&quot;<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#37">37</A>  The President has
proposed to increase  funding for this program to $500 million. The issue
remains to be  settled when the Senate eventually takes up the FY 1996 
Labor-HHS-Education appropriations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Goals 2000.</B> House and Senate conservatives exhausted all  attempts
to eliminate funding for the President's major  education initiative during the
1995 session. The House originally zeroed  out funding for the program, but
Senator Arlen Specter (R-PA)  succeeded in restoring roughly $310 million.
Several attempts  were made to amend and redirect funds allocated for the
program;  however, the Senate failed several times, because of Democratic  fili
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 39 -->  busters, to bring the
Labor-HHS-Education appropriation to  the floor for consideration. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>AmeriCorps.</B> House and Senate Republicans eliminated all  funding for
the President's national service program during the 1995  session. The
President, however, on December 19 vetoed the  VA/HUD appropriations bill, to
which the program was attached. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997 </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The evidence demonstrates that reform based on increased  and equalized
spending, higher teacher salaries, smaller classes,  and similar marginal
changes does not work because these factors  are not related to school
performance or student achievement.  Only fundamental reform centered around
school choice can reverse  the deteriorating performance of our schools and the
declining  academic achievement of our children. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Expand parental choice at the state level. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Parents should be allowed to choose any public, private, or 
religious school<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#38">38</A> for their
children, with the per-capita portion  of state education funds for each child
going to the chosen  school. This could be achieved directly by granting parents
a voucher  for each child,<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#39">39</A> or by
the state's allocating directly to each school  the per capita portion of
education funds for each child the school  enrolls. Alternatively, parents could
receive tuition tax credits, up  to the per capita state education amount, for
tuition payments to  any private, public, or religious school, with the public
schools  restructured to receive their financing through such payments, or 
vouchers could be provided to lower-income (and tuition tax credits  to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 40 -->  higher-income) families.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Foster school autonomy at the state level.</B> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>If America is to encourage true reform in the public  schools,
school autonomy must go hand in hand with parental choice.  This will give
schools the ability to change. School autonomy  means that the principal,
administrative staff, and teachers in each  local public school, perhaps with
parents as representatives, would  be free to run their school as they choose:
to select their own  curriculum, textbooks, staff, and teachers (which means
that teacher  certification requirements must be relaxed or abolished 
outright). Regulation of private schools also must be relaxed to the  absolute
minimum. In this way, parental choice can create an effective  market that
controls and regulates schools in accordance with the  preferences of parents
rather than according to the whims of a  bureaucratic elite.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Eliminate the U.S. Department of Education.</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>American taxpayers do not need a federal Department of 
Education. In preparing to shut down the federal government in  November 1995,
before President Clinton's veto of the second  continuing resolution to keep
federal agencies operating, the Clinton  Administration made a distinction
between &quot;essential&quot; employees,  who would remain on the job, and &quot;non-essential&quot;
employees,  who would be furloughed. The Clinton Administration determined  that
4,394 of the Department of Education's 4,937 employees   89 percent  were &quot;non-essential&quot;
and thus would be furloughed  for the duration of the budget impasse.<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#40">40</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 41 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Created by Congress at the request of President Jimmy Carter  in 1979, not
yet two decades old, the U.S. Department of  Education is doing precisely what
its severest critics envisioned:  usurping local and state control by slowly and
steadily introducing  federal controls. Although it accounts for about six
percent of total  public funding of education, its influence is out of all
proportion to  its financial role. Indeed, the Department of Education inserts 
itself into almost all aspects of the day-to-day workings of the  nation's
15,025 school districts. Bureaucratic, heavy-handed and  intrusive, it is a
metaphor for many of Washington's most wasteful  and meddlesome domestic
programs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Yet the most alarming aspect of the growing federal control  of education is
not administrative interference, but its adverse  impact on academic
performance, equally the product of sins of  omission and commission. The
increasing power of special interests,  the burgeoning size of school districts,
the refusal of the  public schools to submit to any market discipline, weakening
 community bonds, a pervasive anti-intellectualism in schools of  education,
general permissiveness, family dissolution  all have played  a role. At no time
in American history has academic  performance been more important. Yet as the
federal role increases,  education performance declines. The new federal role in
education  obviously was not intended to impair academic performance, but, 
steadily and almost without interruption, student academic  performance
nevertheless has fallen, and the Department of Education has  done nothing to
stop the downward spiral. While cause and effect  may be elusive, and the
department's supporters assert a variety  of causes to explain the decline in
student performance,  these changes occurred during, and as a part of, the
federal  ascendancy in American education.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 42 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Conservative candidates must explain that Washington's role  is designed to &quot;federalize&quot;
the nation's schools. It is designed  to make them march to a common drum beat,
and it is succeeding   to the detriment of our children's education.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Conservative candidates should seek to dismantle all federal  agencies that
do not serve the public interest. The most visible  example is the U.S.
Department of Education. Conceptually, as former  Secretaries William Bennett
and Lamar Alexander, and former  Assistant Secretary Chester E. Finn have noted,
the federal  government should:<A HREF="ftnt9.htm#41">41</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     Recognize that education in America is &quot;the
constitutional  responsibility of the states, the social responsibility of
communities,  and the moral responsibility of families&quot;;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     &quot;Except when the civil rights of individuals are
menaced...  never impede the capacity of families, communities and states to 
decide how best to provide education to their children&quot;;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Use the bully pulpit as appropriate but recognize that goals 
and standards must always be truly voluntary and that federal  funds should not
be used as &quot;carrots&quot; or &quot;sticks&quot; in ways that  effectively
diminish state and local control; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     &quot;[D]edicate itself to (a) fostering family responsibility
and  local control, (b) assisting states to fulfill their responsibilities as 
they see fit, (c) providing sound statistics, prompt and accurate  assessment
results and other information, and (d) safeguarding  individuals from illegal
discrimination.&quot;
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 43 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>To send responsibility home where it belongs, to transfer  legitimate
federal functions to other federal agencies, and to  eliminate what is
unnecessary is the job for Congress. For example:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>-     The protection of the civil rights of all Americans
should be  enforced by the U.S. Department of Justice, as they are in the 
larger society, rather than by a separate (and redundant) Office of  Civil
Rights in an Education Department;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Data collection, dissemination, analysis, and research should  be
transferred to a Central office of Data Collection in the Bureau  of the Census;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     Aid to poor children in elementary and secondary schools (Title 
1/Chapter 1 money) should be made available to poor  youngsters either as a
transfer payment on their behalf or as an  education voucher, negotiable in any
school that satisfies a state's  compulsory attendance statutes, without
reference to whether the school  is public or private, secular or denominational
(as is the case in  all other industrialized democracies), and with
administrative  responsibility transferred to the states;<A
HREF="ftnt9.htm#42">42</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     College financial aid should be moved to HHS for the  immediate future
and should be merit-based as well as needs-based (as it is  in every other
industrialized democracy); and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>-     All remaining funds should be made available as a  comprehensive block
grant to the states, to be phased out slowly.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Reform the District of Columbia's Public Schools</B>
</P>
<P>In light of the District's unwillingness and inability to govern  its 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 44 -->  schools responsibly, and given
the importance of the city as  the nation's capital, Congress has a
responsibility to act as an 
<U>in lieu </U>state legislature for the District of Columbia. Congress  should
implement a comprehensive set of reforms for the D.C.  public schools, in effect
resurrecting the amendment offered by  Representative Gunderson during the 1995
session. The reform act should:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Authorize the establishment of independent public charter 
schools,</B> using existing D.C. public and private schools as well as  new
schools created with the help of universities in the District. It  also should
authorize many federal institutions within D.C.,  including the National Science
Foundation and Smithsonian Institution,  to help establish public charter
schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Establish charter schools which would help restructure the  existing
public school system,</B> allowing innovative school principals  and teachers to
work with parents and academic institutions to  overhaul the system.
Lower-income parents would have the right  to choose an effective private school
if they are not satisfied  with their child's public school. This would hold the
public schools  to account.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Provide scholarships of up to $3,000 for students</B> whose  family
income is at or below the poverty level and up to $1,500 for  students whose
family income is not more than 185 percent above  the poverty level. These
scholarships would allow low-income  D.C. families to send their children to any
private, independent,  religious or non-religious school located in the District
of  Columbia and the surrounding counties of Northern Virginia and  Maryland.
They would cover the cost of fees and other expenses for  tutoring and
instructional services after school hours and the costs of  trans
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 45 -->  portation for a student enrolled
in a District of Columbia  public school, public charter school, or private
school participating in  the tuition scholarship program. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Establish a special panel to develop tests to monitor the  progress</B>
of the District's schools so that parents have real information  with which to
evaluate D.C.'s schools. This &quot;World Class  Schools Panel&quot; would be
responsible for developing a core curriculum  for kindergarten through 12th
grade. In addition, it would  encourage more private-sector involvement in the
District's schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>It is essential that this education proposal not tell D.C.  residents what
schools they must have. Rather, it must create the  conditions and incentives
for change. It would still be up to parents,  teachers, principals, and District
institutions to take advantage of this  opportunity.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For Congress to bring about real reform for America's schools,  it must
first set a precedent by reforming the schools in its  backyard. Congress could
achieve this by attaching these reforms as  an amendment to the District's 1997
appropriations bill. This  would force the President and liberal Democrats in
Congress to hold  up the District's funding as the price for continuing to
oppose  real reform for the children who most need it.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Enact a Low-Income School Choice Demonstration.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Representatives Frank Riggs (R-CA) and Dave Weldon (R-FL)  co-sponsored
voucher legislation in 1995 (H.R. 1640) similar to  a bipartisan bill (S. 618)
introduced by Senators Dan Coates  (R-IN) and Joseph Lieberman (R-CT). This
legislation, not yet  enacted, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 46 -->  would allow any K-12 child
eligible to participate in the free  or reduced-price National School Lunch
Program to receive  vouchers to attend the public or private school of the
family's choice.  The bill would authorize grants for 10 to 20 low-income 
communities to establish voucher-based school choice programs at a cost of  $30
million over three years. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Doesn't education choice mean the brightest and most  affluent
students will escape, leaving the poorest and most difficult to  educate trapped
in bad public schools?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The exodus of the brightest and richest students happens  under
the current system because only they have the ability to  choose. Comprehensive
school choice gives poor inner-city children  the same freedom to choose their
schools that wealthier children  already enjoy.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>School choice improves all schools and benefits all children,  not just
those who change schools. The reason?  Competition forces  all schools to strive
to perform better in order to survive. This  has been the experience in East
Harlem, for instance, where  school choice proved especially beneficial to poor
minority  inner-city students.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Don't we need the public schools to teach all students a  common set
of basic values, beliefs, and democratic principles?   Doesn't choice leads to
diverse, fragmented philosophies  and views?
</B><!-- Generation of PM publication page 47 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The public schools are not teaching a common set of  values,
beliefs, and principles. Many are teaching moral relativism  and
multiculturalism. Under comprehensive school choice,  schools must reflect the
values, beliefs, and principles common to  parents in order to attract students
and funds. The parents of each  child, not government bureaucrats and
politicians, should have the  final say over what that child is taught.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Won't school choice encourage extremists or fanatics to set  up
bizarre &quot;cult&quot; schools and possibly even lead to such abuses as  the
indoctrination of students in Satan worship or racial supremacy?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Under a program of school choice, schools would have to  meet
minimum certification requirements, just as private schools  do today. Such
requirements effectively preclude extremist or  cult schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. With vouchers, wouldn't private schools receive  government money,
and so private schools would face heavy regulatory  control?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> No private school is required to participate in any school 
choice program. Private schools which receive no state funds today  would be
free to forego state funds under choice programs, leaving  them no worse off
than they are now. One of the fundamental  principles of comprehensive school
choice is autonomy, with each  school free to operate as it chooses. Choice
means reducing the  regulation of public schools to the minimum level now
applied to  private schools, not increasing regulation of private schools.
</P>
<P>
</P>
