<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"><br>
<h3>Resource Bank</h3><p>
From the September Edition of <i>The Insider</i><br>

<h2>Magazines & Journals</h2><p>

</center>
<P>
<I><B>Policy Review: The Journal of American Citizenship</B></I><BR>
<a href="/heritage/p_review/nov96/toc.html">November/December 1996</a>, The Heritage Foundation
<hr><p>
<dd>The cover story of this issue, <a href="/heritage/p_review/nov96/shokraii.html">"Free at Last: Black America Signs Up for School Choice</a>," by Nina Shokraii, examines the growing support for school choice amongst African-Americans. Most black political leaders actively oppose vouchers and charter schools, yet their constituents are looking more and more to options other than decaying public schools ---which have a disasterous record of teaching black children. Shokraii, Director of Outreach Programs at the Institute for Justice, documents the school choice movements in black communities in Milwaukee and Cleveland, and charter school movements in California and Michigan. It is quite evident that standards, discipline, and parental involvement of private or charter schools are bringing more black parents to fight for schools choice. Shokraii concludes that school choice and charter schools are becoming the civil rights movement of the 1990s. This issue also includes the following articles: <a href="/heritage/p_review/nov96/symp.html">"Welfare Reform: Can the States Fly Solo?"</a> by Eloise Anderson, Vance McMahan, Don Taylor and Jason Turner; <a href="/heritage/p_review/nov96/lungren.html">"Three Cheers for Three Strikes</a>," by California Attorney General Dan Lungren; and <a href="/heritage/p_review/nov96/radan.html">"The Freshman's First Principles</a>," by Rep. George Radanovich.  64 pp. CONTACT: Policy Review, The Heritage Foundation, 214 Massachusetts Avenue, N.E., Washington, D.C. 20002-4999, 202/546-4400, Email <a href="mailto: polrev@heritage.org">polrev@heritage.org</a> Internet <a href="/heritage">http://www.heritage.org</a>.
<p>
<B><I>Reason</I></B><br>
December 1996, Reason Foundation<hr><p>
<dd>Topics include: why fishermen who used to welcome the Coast Guard have started to dread it; why reports of the death of the American Dream are greatly exaggerated; a special book review section featuring several authors lists of books about technology; and the Consumer Product Safety Commision's interference with children's baseball. 74 pp. CONTACT: Reason Foundation, 3415 South Sepulveda Boulevard, Suite 400, Los Angeles, CA 90034, 310/391-2245, fax 310/391-4395, Internet <a href=" http://www.reason.org">http://www.reason.org</a>.
<p>
<B><I>PERC Reports</I></B><br>

September 1996, PERC<hr><p>
<dd>
This issue features an article entitled "How Traditional Conservatives View Free Market Environmentalism," by John Bliese. Mr. Bliese, an Associate Professor of Communication Studies at Texas Tech University, presents the traditionalist school of conservatism's view of "free market environmentalism." Also included are the following articles: "Fact vs. Perception: What Students Think About Forests," by Jim Bowyer, Professor of Forest Products and Director of the Forest Products Managment Development Institute at the University of Minnesota; and "Beyond the Rangeland Conflict: The Gray Ranch," by Dan Dagget, among other articles. 20 pp. CONTACT: PERC, 502 South 19th Avenue, Suite 211, Bozeman, MT 59715, 406/587-9591, fax 406/586-7555, e-mail <a href="mailto: perc@perc.org ">perc@perc.org</a>.
<p>
<B><I>Regulation</I></B><br>
1996, No. 3, Cato Institute<hr><p>
<dd>
Articles include: "Clinton's Regulatory Record," by William Niskanen, Chairman of the Cato Institute; "Reviewing the National Performance Review," by George Nesterczuk, Majority Staff Director for the Civil Service Subcommittee of the Committee on Government Reform and Oversight; "Telecommunications Act of 1996," by Lawrence Gasman, Director of Telecommunications and Technology Studies at the Cato Institute; "Proposition 211," by Susan Woodward, Chief Economist at the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission from 1992-95; and "Electric Utility Reform," by Jerry Taylor, Director of Natural Resource Studies at the Cato Institute. 79 pp. CONTACT: Cato Institute, 1000 Massachusetts Avenue, N.W., Washington, D.C. 20001, 202/842-0200, fax 202/842-3490, e-mail <a href="mailto: cato@cato.org ">cato@cato.org</a>, Internet <a href=" http://www.cato.org">http://www.cato.org</a>.
<p>
<B><I>Crisis</I></B><br>
Novemember 1996<hr><p>
<dd>
A notable article in this month's issue of <I>Crisis</I> discusses the bad economics of the pastoral letter of America's Catholic bishops, <I>Economic Justice for All</I>. Michael Joyce, President and CEO of the Bradley Foundation, contrasts <I>Economic Justice for All</I> with Pope John Paul II's <I>Centesimus Annus</I>. At the core of the comparison is how the respective writings proscribe ways to help those in need. Joyce points out the bishop's pastoral has much to say about the needy, but nothing to say to them. The letter calls for "an economy that truly respects persons," and even proposes measures to be taken by government as specific as a Targeted Jobs Tax Credit Act. It calls for reforming social sytems in order to secure dignity for the needy, yet it never lists an action or task for the needy themselves. Joyce argues that <I>Centesimus Annus</I> cannot be read without a clear sense that the human person, made in the image and likeness of God, is not quite so subordinate. While the Pope acknowledges that there is a need for political, economic, social, and cultural commitment to the poor, he maintains that the decisive commitment must be made within the heart and conscience of the human person and not depend on asking government or other institution to solve the problem. 60 pp.  CONTACT: 800/852-9962. 

